<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tightened Budget Hurts Zimbabwean Cops: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Reduced Budget has compromised
the efficiency of the Zimbabwe Republic Police (ZRP) in carrying
out its duties, Zimbabwe Home Affairs Minister Dumiso Dagenwa said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Low morals among police officers, coupled with reduced
efficiency and effectiveness is a recipe for corruption,"Dagenwa
said when officially opening an institutional security management
and crime prevention seminar.
</P>
<P>
The police has been allocated only 2.4 billion Zimbabwean
dollars (US$63 million) for the fiscal year ending December, which
falls far short of the force's demands with the spiralling
inflation.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the harsh economic conditions in the country
characterized by massive retrenchments had also resulted in
increased criminal activity as most people were failing to get
decent jobs.
</P>
<P>
He said the cessation of hostilities in the region had resulted
in a large number of fire arms finding their way into Zimbabwe and
these were being used to commit crimes like armed robberies.
</P>
<P>
The strategic location of Zimbabwe, he said, while being an
attractive destination for tourists, had also seen an upsurge of
criminal activities like drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The five-day workshop was being attended by security
representatives from Nigeria, South Africa, Zimbabwe and Interpol
and observers from the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
