<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Reshuffles Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi Monday announced a major cabinet reshuffle, cutting the number
of ministries from 27 to 15, in an effort to streamline his
government and to recover the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Chris Okemo, who was appointed on August 18,
remains his new role, and Foreign Minister Bonaya Godana still
retains his post, local sources said.
</P>
<P>
Former Agriculture Minister Musalia Mudavadi has been moved to
the ministry of Information, Transport and Communications, and his
post is replaced by Chris Obure, former minister for Cooperative
Development.
</P>
<P>
Former Minister Nicholas Biwott of East African and Regional
Cooperation becomes the Minister of Tourism, Trade and Industry,
and George Saitoti remains the vice-president.
</P>
<P>
President Moi said he made the changes in the cabinet in a bid
to "put in place the right conditions for our economic recovery."
</P>
<P>
Local media said that the rearrangement of the cabinet and
civil service meant Moi would sacrifice those who are in the
cabinet purely because they are political allies or because
political reasons demanded their communities be represented in
the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Some economists widely considered the reshuffle was made under
pressure from the World Bank and international donors to trim the
government, curb corruption and improve the economy.
</P>
<P>
Since this year, Moi has made several cabinet reshuffles, major
or minor,
</P>
<P>
in order to stop the plunged economy and build confidence in the
economy and overseas investors and donors.
</P>
<P>
In July, Moi appointed Richard Leakey as the head of civil
service and cabinet secretary, and several private sector
technocrats to government posts in a bid to revamp the economy.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Moi ordered unpopular Finance Minister Francis
Masakhalia and Energy Minister Chris Okemo swapped portfolios.
</P>
<P>
As Okemo, a Canadian-trained economist, became new Finance
Minister, some analysts said that the Kenyan government was
trying to strengthen its commitment to restoring relations with
donors, especially with the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
which suspended a 205-million-U.S. dollar loan two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's economy is declined rapidly after the IMF cut all loans
to the country in July, 1997 on grounds of widespread corruption
and poor governance.
</P>
<P>
The country's economic growth dropped from 4.6 percent in 1996
to 2.3 percent in 1997 and 1.8 percent in 1998. It is expected to
be even lower this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
