<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Differences Won't Affect Jordanian-Kuwaiti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah
Bin Hussein told the press here Monday that past differences will
not affect the development of relations between Jordan and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival for a two-day official visit, Abdullah also said
the visit was "the start of a new page in the history of the long
and deep relations between the two states, and will develop in the
interests of both the Kuwaiti and Jordanian people."
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, the first Jordanian monarch to visit Kuwait in more
than nine years, is scheduled to hold talks with Kuwaiti Emir
Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah and other senior officials on bilateral
ties as well as a number of other issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Although Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah had
ruled out any specific agenda for the bilateral talks, earlier
local reports said issues such as the Jordanian labor,
compensation claims might be touched upon.
</P>
<P>
Since Jordan showed sympathy with Iraq during the 1991 Gulf
War triggered by Iraq's invasion and occupation of Kuwait, Kuwait
estranged its ties with Amman after the war, thus resulting in the
forced return of tens of thousands of Jordanian workers who used
to work in the Gulf emirate.
</P>
<P>
But Kuwait appears not to be ready to accept Jordanian workers
in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti officials also denied allegations that Jordan had made
official compensation claims for the Jordanian laborers.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Jordan have been improving their relations over the
past two years, which was marked by a number of medium and
high-level exchange visits.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime Minister Saad Abdullah Al-Sabah
went to Amman last February to attend the funeral of the late
Jordanian King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Amman reopened its embassy in Kuwait last March, when Jordan's
Foreign Minister Abdul Ilah Al-Khatib paid an official visit here,
marking a restoration of ties.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, the Jordanian cabinet approved Mohammed Al-Mufdhi
Al-Qaraan as Jordan's new ambassador to Kuwait, the first since
the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
While Abdullah is widely believed to be here to crown the
current rapprochement between the two countries, political
observers here have not ruled out that "Kuwait aims to further
isolate Iraq by warming up its ties with Jordan, Baghdad's
long-time ally." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
