<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Claims Strikes No Threat to Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Last year's strikes,
which caused the loss of 3.8 million work days, should not be seen
as a threat by investors, Labor Minister Membathisi Mdladlana said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The Labour Relations Act is making sure there is certainty in
the labour market. There is certainty for investors in South
Africa." Membathisi said when speaking here at the release of the
Labor Department's annual report on industrial action.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government was focusing on maintaining
existing jobs and short-term job creation projects.
</P>
<P>
The Commission for Conciliation, Mediation and Arbitration
(CCMA) annual report was also released on Monday, and Vincent
Mntambo was announced as the new chairman.
</P>
<P>
The minister commended the CCMA for improving dispute
resolution, saying that "faced with a 35 percent increase in its
caseload in this period, the CCMA was nevertheless still able to
achieve a settlement rate of 71 percent. "
</P>
<P>
It had also made a broader contribution to labor market
stability, he said, adding that 58 percent of mutual interest
disputes that could have resulted in strikes were settled through
conciliation by the CCMA.
</P>
<P>
A total of 527 strikes took place in South Africa last year,
involving 3. 2 million workers with the lost wages estimated at
48.3 million rands (8 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Most of these strikes were over wages, followed by disputes
over retrenchments.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector lost the most work days, followed by
the financial services industry and mining.
</P>
<P>
The average strike was seven days long and the longest was 86
days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
