<HEADLINE> Turkey Must be Included in Balkan Reconstruction Plans, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Greek Development Minister
Evangelos Venizelos said Monday that Turkey must be included in
the Balkan reconstruction plans in order to heal the wounds caused
by last month's devastating earthquake in northwestern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a conference on international conflicts in the
northern Greek city of Thessaloniki, Venizelos said that
reconstruction must include the entire southern Balkans, of course
including Turkey, but the neighboring country's inclusion in these
plans had to be under certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
He said that Greece could play an active and very important
role not only through the community or in partnership with other
countries, but also with its own unilateral initiatives.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) leaders decided late June to base its
agency for the Balkan reconstruction in Thessaloniki, the largest
city in northern Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greece, which has a tense relations with Turkey over their
disputes in the Aegean Sea and the Cyprus problem, has repeatedly
said that it will not lift its veto on the more than 1-billion
U.S. dollars EU financial aid to Ankara unless the latter improves
its human rights record and its relations with Athens.
</P>
<P>
To ease its strained ties with Turkey, Greece Sunday welcomed
acceptance by the EU foreign ministers of its proposal that Turkey
should receive reconstruction aid after the earthquake from the
15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
The aid was reported to be nearly 200 million euros in the form
of grants and another 600 million euros in loans from the European
Investment Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
