<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP to Assess Environment Impact in Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Environment Program
(UNEP) and U.N. Centre for Human Settlements (Habitat) will send
a new group of task force for Serbia and Montenegro Tuesday for
technical assessment of the environmental impact caused by the
Balkans conflict.
</P>
<P>
The mission of five scientists from Austria, Bulgaria, Denmark,
Norway and Slovakia will assess the damages to biological
diversity in the protected areas in the region, said a release
issued by UNEP and Habitat in Kenyan capital Nairobi Monday.
</P>
<P>
The experts are scheduled to visit Fruska Gora National Park
near Novi Sad, Kopaonik national park, Zlatibor, and Lake Skadar
in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
It has been reported that the conflict may have had a direct
impact on plant and animal populations in these protected areas
with possible negative consequences for the region's biological
diversity.
</P>
<P>
The release said the new mission will gather relevant
information on the pro-conflict status of these areas and visit
selected sites for assessing first-hand the current situation.
</P>
<P>
In July and August, UNEP and Habitat sent their missions of
international experts to Yugoslavia and Serbia to assess the
environmental damages at selected industrial sites and the
possible impact on the River Danube.
</P>
<P>
At present, a Balkans Task Force mission is working in Kosovo
on issues of urban management and rehabilitation, housing law,
property registration and environmental management, the release
said.
</P>
<P>
UNEP said a final report on the work of the Balkans Task Force,
 containing all the scientific findings and some possible
proposals, will be submitted to the U.N. Secretary-General.
</P>
<P>
The Balkans Task Force was established by Klaus Toepfer, U.N.
Under Secretary-General, and the head of UNEP and Habitat in May,
aiming at assessing the environmental and human settlements
impacts of the Balkans conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
