<HEADLINE> Nominating U.S. Envoy to Sudan "Unsound": Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Nominating a U.S. envy to
Sudan is a "unsound" way in solving problems facing the north
African nation, a Sudanese government official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The official, who declined to be named, said that the U.S. move
disturbs the the ongoing efforts to organize the life-line relief
program between the Sudanese government and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Reports saying Sudan was not against the nomination of a
U.S. special envoy were inaccurate, said the official, adding that
his country was reserved on the way of the nomination.
</P>
<P>
It also goes against the peace initiative of the
Intergovernmental Authority of Development (IGAD) in which the
United States itself takes part through the IGAD partnership, the
official asserted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Sudanese government was not consulted
but simply informed. Thereby it will keep an eye on and assess the
situation before making a decision on dealing with the U.S. envoy.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Sudanese Human Rights Organization Ahmed Al-Nasri
had expressed, according to press reports Sunday, his country's
readiness to receive and cooperate with the U.S. envoy in case his
agenda did not infringe on Sudan's sovereignty and territorial
integrity and the Khartoum peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government has criticized the U.S. move as an
"arrogant" decision.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton appointed Harry Johnston as special
envoy to Sudan in August. Johnston was Chairman of a subcommittee
on Africa when he served in the Congress. He is assigned to push
Sudan to improve its human record and try to end the 16-year civil
war.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. considers Sudan a sponsor of terrorism and has imposed
economic and military sanctions on it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
