<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Opposition Calls for Political Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian opposition parties,
human rights organizations, politicians and professionals launched
a campaign Monday calling for political and constitutional reforms
to turn Egypt into a parliamentary republic.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the country's four leading opposition parties
submitted an appeal to President Hosni Mubarak, demanding the
reforms, the campaign's preparatory committee said in a news
conference held at the headquarters of the Egyptian Organization
for Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
The appeal called for an "end to the state of emergency,
release of political detainees and pardoning of all political
prisoners held on nonviolent charges."
</P>
<P>
The appeal also called for providing safeguards for free
elections, the freedom to set up political parties, freedom to
establish and possess newspapers and guarantees for the
independence of trade unions and professional syndicates.
</P>
<P>
The organizers said they will begin a campaign to collect
signatures in support for their demands and will hold a public
meeting on September 22 to garner support from the people.
</P>
<P>
They said their reforms are aimed at transferring Egypt into a
parliamentary republic in which "the people would be the source of
all power."
</P>
<P>
The planned September 22 gathering will come four days before a
public referendum to formally approve Mubarak's June 2 nomination
by parliament for a fourth six-year term in office.
</P>
<P>
Under Egypt's constitution, the People's Assembly (Parliament),
which is dominated by Mubarak's ruling National Democratic Party,
nominates presidential candidates. Egyptians are then asked in a
referendum whether they support the candidate, and can vote only
"yes" or "no."
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties consider the nomination of a single
candidate undemocratic because it leaves Egyptians with no choice
in electing their president.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who was vice president of late President Anwar Sadat,
was first elected president in 1981 after Sadat's assassination by
Islamic radicals. He was re-nominated unopposed by the parliament
in 1987 and 1993 and secured an overwhelming number of "yes" votes
in the referendums. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
