<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Organized Crime on Rise in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Organized crime is on the
increase in Britain and there are not enough funds to fight it,
the head of a national law enforcement agency warned on Monday.
</P>
<P>
John Abbot, director general of the National Criminal
Intelligence Service (NCIS), said some 25 million pounds (about 40
million U.S. dollars) are needed over the next three years to
combat the growing threat from increasingly professional gangs.
</P>
<P>
He said criminal intelligence helped closed heroin and crack
cocaine factories, with 350 million pounds (560 million dollars)
of illegal drugs seized last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts at NCIS also warned there were indications that
organized criminal gangs were beginning to operate in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Ian Morrison, head of NCIS's south-east region, warned that the
growing number of asylum seekers from the Balkans could help the
gangs target Britain.
</P>
<P>
NCIS said organized criminals were already deeply involved in
people-smuggling, because it provided high profits with little
risk compared with drug trafficking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
