<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Refutes U.S. Allegations of Developing Banned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Monday dismissed as
lies the U.S. allegations that it is still developing weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Iraqi Information Ministry said in a
statement that the U.S. allegations written in the six-page report
of the White House "do not stand on solid bases."
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the U.S. government recently submitted
a six-page report to the Congress, which accuses Iraq of
continuing to develop weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that all the information in the U.S. report
is old and taken from previous reports of the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) and the International Atomic Energy Agency
(IAEA) in charge of destroying Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The timing of this report and the publishing of parts of it in
Washington Post and New York Times coincide with the feverish
media campaign waged against Iraq by the U.S., said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that the U.S. waged this political and media
campaign against Iraq in order to blur facts and prepare the
ground for the British-Dutch proposal which had been rejected by
the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the Netherlands in June proposed to the Security
Council that the sanctions on Iraq be lifted after Iraq fully
cooperates with an enlarged body of weapons inspectors which will
replace UNSCOM and carry out more intrusive inspections of Iraq's
banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the U.S. report tried to deceive the
international community that all Iraq's weapon files are still
open which will lead to the resumption of weapons inspection and
the return of U.N. weapons inspectors to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of weapons inspections will mean the resumption
of espionage activities for the CIA, said the spokesman, adding
that this attempt will be totally rejected by Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
