<HEADLINE> S. African States Urged to Protect Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Vice President
Omar Ali Juma Monday called the southern African countries to
protect environment, as problems arising from the sector have
caused heavy social and economic loss in the region.
</P>
<P>
Juma made the remarks in the Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam
while opening the Third Regional Training Session for Cohort 7 of
the Leadership for Environment and Development (LEAD) Southern
Africa Chapter.
</P>
<P>
In a speech read on his behalf by Permanent Secretary in the
Vice President's Office Peter Ngumbullu, Juma said the process of
dealing with environmental problems must involve all stakeholders
through national and regional capacity mobilization.
</P>
<P>
There exist direct links between poverty and environmental
degradation, he said, adding that poverty is a habitual cause of
environmental degradation as it undermines people's capacity to
manage resources prudently.
</P>
<P>
"Problems of poverty, ill health and others that plague the
majority of the people in Tanzania and the southern African region
are as much environmental as they are developmental," he said.
</P>
<P>
LEAD is an international organization aimed at safeguarding
environment and promoting sustainable economic development that is
environment friendly.
</P>
<P>
The theme for this training session is "Challenge and Options
for Sustainable Development."
</P>
<P>
It draws mid-career professionals from six Southern African
Development Community (SADC) countries, namely, Zambia, Zimbabwe,
Malawi, Mozambique, South Africa and Tanzania.  
</P>
