<HEADLINE> Angola to Promote Tourism Amidst Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Angola will work hard in the
coming decade to make it an attractive destination for foreign
tourists despite the ongoing decades-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
The southwest African country will pay more attention to
"specialized" tourism such as cultural tourism, sports tourism,
fairs and exhibitions, while continuing to promote the tourism of
natural scenery, parks and reserves, the Ministry of Hotel and
Tourism said in a document available on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, Angola hosted only 52,000 tourists
in 1998 due to the recrudescence of civil war between the
government and the rebel National Union for Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA); even so, it was seven times the number of the
previous year which was only 7, 000.
</P>
<P>
Main hotels registered some 24,000 arrivals, earning 3.4
trillion readjusted kwanzas (about 4 million U.S. dollars) to the
war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Most of the tourists came from Portugal, South Africa, the
United States, Brazil and France, who are mainly for business and
family visits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
