<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Thinktank Urges EU Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A thinktank close to Britain's
Labor government called on Monday for sweeping reforms in the
European Union, noting it needs a new look for the next century
but should abandon attempts to become a superstate.
</P>
<P>
The pro-European Foreign Policy Center, known to have been set
up with the blessing of Prime Minister Tony Blair and Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook, said there was a need for a fresh approach
which would "escape the ghost of federalism" and allow national
identities to flourish.
</P>
<P>
In a new pamphlet, entitled "Network Europe: the new case for
Europe," Author Mark Leonard of the Center said both a federal
superstate and a simple free trade area, favored by British
eurosceptics, were both outdated ideas.
</P>
<P>
Leonard, an intellectual whizz-kid in his mid-20s, became well
known two years ago with an influential pamphlet which called for
the "rebranding" of Britain, a Reuters report said. said.
</P>
<P>
Instead of increasing the powers of the European parliament or
electing the European Commission, the bloc should hold
cross-border referendums and should set up a new council of deputy
prime ministers to run its business, it said.
</P>
<P>
"At present, the EU is good at representing countries and
special interests, but not citizens," Leonard wrote, arguing that
the six-month rotating presidency should be scrapped in favor of
an presidency of three states elected by all members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
