<HEADLINE> Lebanese Doctors Sentenced for Negligence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 6 (Xinhua) -- In an unprecedented move,
Lebanon's military court Monday sentenced three doctors each to
prison terms of five days on charge of negligence, an action
which stirred uproar among the country's medical community.
</P>
<P>
The military tribunal headed by Brig. Gen. Maher Safieddin said
that the three doctors from two hospitals were held responsible
for the death of Khalil Hamad, a 33-year old army sergeant and
father of three.
</P>
<P>
It said that their negligence during the work caused his
death.
</P>
<P>
The trial was the first of its kind in Lebanon's military
court history because the country does not have laws that pertain
specifically to medical malpractice and dissatisfied patients or
their families usually have to resort to the civil courts.
</P>
<P>
The trial sparked strong protest and criticism from the
country's medical associations.
</P>
<P>
Ghattas Khouryt, the head of Medical Syndicate for Beirut and
North Lebanon, said, "we are not against doctors facing up to their
responsibilities, but we don't accept that they be treated like
criminals."
</P>
<P>
"We're against their arrest, because we know this will create a
crisis between doctors and patients," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
