<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Tiptoes Through Moral Minefield Over Teen Births </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Labor government,
torn between its strong views on morality and fears of repeating
its predecessor's mistakes, tiptoed carefully on Monday around the
explosive issue of how to stop teenage pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Observer newspaper on Sunday, Prime
Minister Tony Blair called for a "new moral purpose" following two
reports of 12-year-olds becoming pregnant, one of them by a
14-year-old boy who blamed too much sex education at his school.
</P>
<P>
His spokesman on Monday denied that Blair was trying to launch
a new moral crusade to rival the ill-fated "back to basics"
initiative of his Conservative predecessor John Major, the Reuters
reported.
</P>
<P>
But he insisted the government had a responsibility to get
involved in cutting Britain's rate of teenage pregnancies, the
highest in Europe. "Call it a moral question if you like," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"It's a real issue which is damaging British society," the
spokesman said, referring to Blair's concern over teenage
behavior. "It is something that has been part of his political
agenda the whole way through."
</P>
<P>
But he denied Blair, whose government is lowering the age of
consent for homosexuals from 18 to 16, wanted to turn the clock
back and reimpose a Victorian moral order, as demanded by some
rightwing commentators.
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Jack Straw also rejected the idea of the
government preaching sexual morality, stressing that it wanted to
protect and help children rather than lecture adults.
</P>
<P>
Blair's government has toughened the law to make parents take
responsibility for their children and allow local authorities and
police to keep young criminals off the streets with curfews.
</P>
<P>
But the new legal powers have only rarely been used, leaving
the government apparently powerless to change behavior patterns
through exhortation alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
