<HEADLINE> NatWest Announces L&AMP;G Takeover Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The UK's National Westminster
Bank Monday announced a 10.75 billion pounds agreed bid for
British life insurer and fund manager Legal &AMP; General Plc,
creating a new British financial giant.
</P>
<P>
The bid is the second big UK bank-assurance takeover. Less than
three months ago the UK's largest bank, Lloyds TSB, said it would
buy mutual life and pensions group Scottish Widows for 7.0 billion
pounds.
</P>
<P>
David Rowland, chairman of NatWest, called it a "vital
strategic move by NatWest", saying that "Legal &AMP; General was a
group with "strong management, a great record and excellent
prospects."
</P>
<P>
The deal is expected to generate pre-tax cost savings of at
least 130 million pounds a year by the end of 2002, largely
through integrating NatWest Life operations into L&AMP;G.
</P>
<P>
After the deal NatWest shareholders would own about 75 percent
of the enlarged group and L&AMP;G shareholders would own the remaining
25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Rowland and his Chief Executive Derek Wanless will retain their
positions in the enlarged group. L&AMP;G's chief executive Prosser
will become deputy chairman, responsible for retail banking, life
assurance, pensions and fund management.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to spark a fresh wave of merger activity
with fellow potential targets, such as Norwich Union, seeing share
prices rising sharply on the announcement.
</P>
<P>
Finance trade union said it feared the takeover would mean job
losses and demanded immediate talks with management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
