<HEADLINE> NATO Continues Aggression Against Yugoslavia After Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Ambassador to the
United Nations Office Branko Brankovic on Monday accused NATO of
continuing its aggression against Yugoslavia by other means such
as an economic war, a war of propaganda and an underground war
through subversive actions after the end of the military
aggression.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador, speaking to reporters here, said that the crime
against peace and humanity "is the greatest crime committed by
NATO and its member states."
</P>
<P>
During the 78-day bombings against Yugoslavia, NATO, under the
leadership of the United States, Brankovic said, over 2,500 people
were killed and the majority of them were women, children and the
elderly, as well as mothers and newborns.
</P>
<P>
"There had been a very loud outcry in the world against NATO
aggression," he said.
</P>
<P>
For example, the Yugoslav ambassador said that even citizens of
the aggressor countries had demanded action, before national or
international courts, against war crimes committed by NATO against
the population of Yugoslavia, such as a group of lawyers from
Canada, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
</P>
<P>
He noted that an Independent Commission of Inquiry Hearing to
Investigate the United States and NATO War Crimes against the
People of Yugoslavia, presided over by former U.S. Attorney
General Ramsey Clark, was established to collect evidence and
indict the 19 leading personalities of the NATO member states.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Brankovic introduced a white book
entitled "NATO Crimes in Yugoslavia, Documentary Evidence"
released recently by the Yugoslav foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav ambassador said that the book, now in two volumes,
covers the period from March 24 to April 25, 1999 and the period
from April 25 to June 10, "was a brutal demonstration of the
attempt to implement the so-called 'new world order'". 
</P>
</TEXT>
