<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Optimistic about Palestinian-Israeli Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia on Monday
expressed optimism about the deal signed by the Palestinians and
Israel in Egypt Saturday night on the implementation of the Wye
accord.
</P>
<P>
In its meeting in Jeddah, the Saudi cabinet voiced hope that
the deal will be turned into tangible results so that the
Palestinian state could be established with Jerusalem as its
capital, the Saudi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet hoped also that the deal will push forward the
peace talks on the Syrian and Lebanese tracks from where they
broke off to ensure the achievement of permanent and comprehensive
peace and to fully protect the Arab rights.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday Palestinian President Yasser Arafat and Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak signed a memorandum on the
implementation of the Wye River Accord in Sharm El-Sheikh, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Under the memo, Israel would complete the troops withdrawals
stipulated by the Wye agreement by January 2000, rather than by
mid-November under the original Wye timetable.
</P>
<P>
According to the deal, Israel and the Palestinians are supposed
to have entered an advance stage of permanent talks by early 2000,
which would help reduce the potential risk of confrontation
between the two sides raised by the troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The deal also provides for the release of 350 Palestinian
prisoners from the Israeli jails by next October, of whom 200
prisoners will be released within days as a first patch.
</P>
<P>
Early October, the Gaza seaport will be launched and safe
passages for the Palestinians between Gaza Strip and the West bank
will be opened according to the deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
