<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vendor Shot Dead For Attempting Mubarak's Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Hussein Mahmoud Solaiman, a
clothing vendor, was shot dead by presidential guards on Monday
when he was attacking Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak with a
sharp tool, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was inspecting industrial projects in Port Said, 180
kilometers northeast of Cairo, at the northern end of the Suez
Canal. On the way to a meeting, he was waving through his car
window to people along the road, a statement released by the
president's office said.
</P>
<P>
Solaiman approached Mubarak's car and attacked the president
with a sharp tool, inflicting a light wound in his arm, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The president's guards fired at Solaiman and killed him, the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian Interior Ministry official later told the news
agency that Solaiman, better known as Al-Arabi Solaiman, was a
graduate of an industrial institute and a resident of Port Said.
</P>
<P>
Solaiman, 40, "had no political affiliations" but "was known
for his impulsive behaviors and recklessness," the official said.
</P>
<P>
After being treated with a disinfectant, Mubarak went on to
deliver a speech in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian television later showed videotape of crowds on the
streets of Port Said cheering Mubarak, but cut away as shots rang
out and did not show the attack.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has survived at least three attempts on his life. The
most serious attack on him came in June 1995 when Muslim militants
fired at his limousine after it was driving out of Addis Ababa
airport of Ethiopia to a summit of the Organization of African
Unity.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's predecessor, President Anwar Sadat, was assassinated
in 1981 by Muslim extremists angered by his signing of a peace
treaty with Israel in 1979. Mubarak, who was Sadat's vice
president, became president after the assassination.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak plays an active role in mediating the peace talks
between Arab countries and Israel, and cracks down severely on the
Muslim extremists who attempt to topple the secular Egyptian
government and install a strict Islamic rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
