<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Review Industrial Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 6 (Xinhua) -- African countries need to
review their industrial relations systems to meet new challenges
posed by changing information technology in the continent,
Malawian High Commissioner to Zimbabwe Jutilan Chizumila said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chizumila was opening a five-day regional workshop on
strengthening the dispute settlement machinery in Southern Africa
attended by labor officials and employers representatives in
Harare.
</P>
<P>
She said the new information technology had removed physical
barriers at workplaces and consequently left both employees and
employers well informed about their labor rights.
</P>
<P>
"The worker, business and government are now better informed
and this I believe calls upon us to review our labor systems to
meet the new challenges," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said fair labor standards based on equity, social justice
and the rule of law promoted industrial peace and harmony which
was important for higher productivity and economic growth of any
country.
</P>
<P>
"With industrialization and development of trade unions and
collective bargaining, the problem of industrial relations has
become increasingly complex," she said.
</P>
<P>
The seminar aimed at equipping participants with a better
understanding of the dynamics of conflict mediation and
arbitration in labor matters.
</P>
<P>
The delegates from Botswana, Egypt, Ethiopia, Ghana, Kenya,
Nigeria, Seychelles, Swaziland and Zimbabwe attended the workshop.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
