<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South African Team Gears up for African Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's huge
sports machine for the All Africa Games rumbled into motion on
Monday with the 560 athletes lining up for the team photo shoot
after which they moved into the Games Village in Alexander.
</P>
<P>
The collective spirit was high after a marathon two days of
queueing up for accreditation, undergoing last-minute fitness and
medical tests and being kitted out in the green and gold.
</P>
<P>
The logistics in terms of assembly, catering and accommodation
for athletes whose total equals the strength of an infantry
batallion has been run at military proportions.
</P>
<P>
The accommodation on the East Bank of Alexander township
received the thumbs up from team members.
</P>
<P>
"The units are cool and clean," said Panda Nelson of women's
hockey. "It's going to be a unique experience. I reckon we could
have a lot of fun staying there."
</P>
<P>
All the sporting codes reported that their competitors were
ready for the continental showpiece that gets under way on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony takes place at the Johannesburg Stadium on
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday the organisers will officially release the names of
top contenders from all over Africa, followed by the team dinner
in the evening.
</P>
<P>
The most noteworthy withdrawal is that of Ethiopia's Haile
Gebrselassie, the world 10,000m record holder who won the IAAF
World title in Seville in stunning fashion.
</P>
<P>
Gebrselassie has badly blistered feet and is on a downward
curve after a tough European season.
</P>
<P>
Paul Tergat of Kenya, who won the silver medal in the 10,000m,
indicated after his arrival in Seville that he would make the trip
to Johannesburg, but he registered some doubt after his race.
</P>
<P>
Top flight athletes competing in the final two IAAF Golden
League meetings in Berlin and Munich next week may be jaded and
opt out of the track and field action.
</P>
<P>
Hezekiel Sepeng, silver medallist in the 800m at Seville who
broke his SA record in 1 minute 42.69 seconds in Brussels last
Friday when he finished second to world champion Wilson Kipketer,
will have to draw from deep reserves for the Games, as will Johan
Botha and high jump record-holder Hestrie Storbeck.
</P>
<P>
There are those, however, who find themselves under less
pressure in terms of commitment and it would be interesting to see
if they arrive in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
These include Mozambique's Maria Mutola, Zambian Samuel Matate
and Kenyans Christopher Kosgei and Japheth Kimutai.
</P>
<P>
Hendrik Ramaala came fourth in the 10,000m in Brussels in 27:43,
68 -- but his tail could be up for a medal in the absence of
Gebrselassie and Tergat.
</P>
<P>
The gymnasts certainly had their tails up for the Games, with
their international season about to get on the boil.
</P>
<P>
They take to the gymnastics hall at Wits University with
Algeria and Egypt their main challengers.
</P>
<P>
"This will be a vital stepping stone to the world gymnastics
championships in China in October," said national coach George
Hriston.
</P>
<P>
"Our performance in China will mean everything -- that's our
only chance of qualifying for the Sydney Olympics next year
because the Africa Games don't count." 
</P>
</TEXT>
