<HEADLINE> Mitchell Reviews N. Irish Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. mediator George Mitchell
said on Monday that his review of the Good Friday agreement will
only focus on forming a power-sharing government and on arms
decommissioning in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The former U.S. senator is at Stormont, near the Northern
Ireland capital Belfast, for talks with the main political parties
in the province.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that there was no question of renegotiating
the accord -- it was now up to Northern Ireland's politicians to "
seize the opportunity for peace."
</P>
<P>
He added that he believed that the review could end the
political stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell arrived in Northern Ireland on midnight Sunday, trying
to revive the peace process after it reached deadlock two months
ago over the disarmament of Catholic and Protestant guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The former U.S. senator, who helped mediate the original Good
Friday accord last year, is expected to carry out a review and see
whether it is now possible to work out a timetable for
disarmament and to appoint a Northern Ireland cabinet including
the main rival parties in the province.
</P>
<P>
So far there is no sign of an easing of the mutual suspicion
that clouds hopes of implementing the Good Friday pact signed in
April 1998.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell is due to meet the main parties on Monday and Tuesday,
and the British and Irish governments on Wednesday, respectively.
</P>
<P>
He will try to mediate between David Trimble's Protestant, pro-
British Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) and Sinn Fein, the political
wing of the Irish Republic Army (IRA) guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The UUP said it will not share power with Sinn Fein unless the
IRA is disarmed.
</P>
<P>
No finishing date has been set for Mitchell's talks, which will
reopen next Monday, but participants hope they will be over soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
