<HEADLINE> Congo Peace Efforts Suffer Setback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Peace efforts in the
war-torn Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) suffered a major
setback on Monday when a rebel leader accused President Laurent
Kabila of violating a peace accord brokered last week.
</P>
<P>
Bazima Karaha, chief negotiator of the Congolese Rally for
Democracy (RCD), issued a veiled warning that hostilities could
resume.
</P>
<P>
The RCD, which has been fighting to depose Kabila since August
1998, has objected to his decision to appoint Lt. Gen Sylvestre
Luesha as head of his armed forces. The decision was announced
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Luesha is an ethnic Mai Mai, who make up one of the groups
meant to be disarmed under a peace deal brokered in Lusaka last
week, Karaha said in an interview published by South African Press
Association. The loose-knit group has clashed with the rebels
during the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Karaha warned that if Luesha were not removed from his post,
"We will carry on and disarm him".
</P>
<P>
A letter voicing the objection was sent to the Joint Military
Commission, which is overseeing the Congo ceasefire, but no reply
had been received, Karaha said.
</P>
<P>
"It is a threat. It is a violation. This man must be disarmed."
</P>
<P>
Karaha added that the ceasefire appeared to be holding.
</P>
<P>
"The guns are silent. We believe this should be the end of the
war in the Congo," he said.
</P>
<P>
Karaha, who flew in to South Africa on Saturday to hold talks
with President Thabo Mbeki, was Kabila's former foreign minister.
He joined the rebels after accusing Kabila of nepotism and
corruption and failing to chart a clear political course.
</P>
<P>
The civil war in the former Zaire, which erupted a year after
Kabila overthrew its former dictator Mobutu Sese Seko, has drawn
in forces from five other countries. Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola
have been propping up Kabila's regime, while Uganda and Rwanda
have been supporting the rebels trying to overthrow him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
