<HEADLINE> Russian Proton Rocket Puts Satellites Into Orbit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A Proton-K booster-rocket on
Monday sent two communications satellites into orbit from the
Baikonur cosmodrome in Kazakhstan, the first launch of a Proton
booster since July 5 when a similar booster rocket crashed in
Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The satellites belong to the Gazkom company, which agreed to
the launch without any modernization of the booster rocket, the
Interfax news agency reported, quoting the press center of the
Khrunichev space center, the manufacturer of the rocket.
</P>
<P>
Gazkom is a company set up by Gazprom gas monopoly and Energia
rocket corporation to design and operate Yamal-100 satellites.
</P>
<P>
The two Yamal-100 satellites, with a service life of 7-10
years, will be placed in a geostationary orbit, Interfax reported.
