<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Hussein Mahmoud Solaiman, a clothing vendor, was shot
dead by presidential guards on Monday when he was attacking
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak with a sharp tool.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was inspecting industrial projects in Port Said, 180
kilometers northeast of Cairo, at the northern end of the Suez
Canal. On the way to a meeting, he was waving through his car
window to people along the road.
</P>
<P>
Solaiman approached Mubarak's car and attacked the president
with a sharp tool, inflicting a light wound in his arm, the
statement said.(BC-Egypt-Mubarak-Assault)
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein told the
press here Monday that past differences will not affect the
development of relations between Jordan and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival for a two-day official visit, Abdullah also said
the visit was "the start of a new page in the history of the long
and deep relations between the two states, and will develop in the
interests of both the Kuwaiti and Jordanian people."
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, the first Jordanian monarch to visit Kuwait in more
than nine years, is scheduled to hold talks with Kuwaiti Emir
Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah and other senior officials on bilateral
ties as well as a number of other issues of mutual concern.
(BC-Kuwait-Jordan-Visit)
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian opposition parties, human rights
organizations, politicians and professionals launched a campaign
Monday calling for political and constitutional reforms to turn
Egypt into a parliamentary republic.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the country's four leading opposition parties
submitted an appeal to President Hosni Mubarak, demanding the
reforms, the campaign's preparatory committee said in a news
conference held at the headquarters of the Egyptian Organization
for Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
The appeal called for an "end to the state of emergency,
release of political detainees and pardoning of all political
prisoners held on nonviolent charges."(BC-Egypt-Opposition)
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq on Monday dismissed as lies the
U.S. allegations that it is still developing weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
