<HEADLINE> Ramos-Horta Calls for International Intervention in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- East Timorese independence
campaigner Jose Ramos-Horta on Monday appealed to the
international community to send troops to the territory as there
is "a faction in the Indonesian army who were behind the carnage
there.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that the U.N. Security Council, the international
community, the United States in particular, Australia, take
concrete action to bring in an international force into East
Timor," the Nobel laureate told CNN in an interview from New York.
</P>
<P>
Last week, East Timor held a referendum and the result showed a
majority of residents there favored independence. But right after
the release of the referendum result, there was eruption of
violence in the area and hundreds of people were thought to be
killed.
</P>
<P>
Ramos-Horta accused the faction in the Indonesian army of being
behind the violence, saying "there is a faction in the Indonesia
army, the army intelligence and the special troops loyal to
(former) president Suharto (who) have economic and financial
interests in East Timor."
</P>
<P>
He called them "hardliners" who "opposed President B.J.
Habibie's policy toward independence." 
</P>
