<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Favors Australian Troops to E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States favors an
Australian offer to help restore peace in violence-racked East
Timor, provided, Indonesia accepts, the White House said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"If Indonesia accepts that offer, we would support an
Australian effort," White House spokesman Barry Toiv said.
</P>
<P>
He said President Bill Clinton spoke by telephone earlier in
the day with Australian Prime Minister John Howard, who put
Australian troops on emergency alert on Monday for possible quick
deployment.
</P>
<P>
Toiv did not say what the United States would do if Indonesia
rejected Australian troops in East Timor where violence erupted
right after a referendum for independence last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
