<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Ready to Resume Early Warning Talks With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia said Monday that it is
ready to resume talks with the U.S. on creating missile attack
early warning centers, the Interfax new agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev will raise the question with his
U.S. counterpart, William Cohen, when the latter visits Moscow on
September 12, Interfax said, quoting a high-ranking Russian
military official.
</P>
<P>
"The time and very possibility of resuming Russian-American
consultations on early warning centers will depend on the outcome
of the talks between the heads of the defense agencies," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
In September 1998 President Boris Yeltsin and President Bill
Clinton agreed to exchange military experts: to send Russians to a
center in Colorado Springs, Colorado, and Americans to a center
near Moscow. The sides were expected to exchange 10 experts.
</P>
<P>
The move was designed to strengthen confidence and prevent
possible unauthorized launches of intercontinental ballistic
missiles related to the Y2K problem, when computers mistaken the
year 2000 for 1900.
</P>
<P>
Military experts from the two countries are to monitor all
intercontinental ballistic missile launches not only in Russia and
the U.S. but in other countries having such arms, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Early warning centers were supposed to be set up before the end
of this autumn, but talks on this issue were frozen by Moscow
after NATO started the 78-day bombing campaign on Yugoslavia on
March 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
