<HEADLINE> Chinese Culture Brings Sensation to Parisians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Since the beginning of the
month, many Parisians have found a small change has taken place in
themselves -- their eyes dazzled by unfamiliar Chinese colors and
their ears resounding with Chinese music tunes.
</P>
<P>
As tens of thousands of people have visited the China Culture
Week in the first half time of its display, the Parisians are
re-discovering a great civilization which they mistakenly thought
that they already knew.
</P>
<P>
Few of the French listeners found the courage to pose a
question to Professor Ma Chengyuan, the Dean of the Shanghai
Museum, when he gave a lecture on Monday on the Golden Age of
Bronzes in the Shang and Zhou Dynasties of China.
</P>
<P>
Listening with great interest, most of the 400-strong audience
found that the stately, elegant and mystic bronze cups, bowls,
music instruments and wine containers are of a too far away
culture from a too far away age.
</P>
<P>
When the visitors saw the set of chime bells from the Warring
States period 2,400 years ago, they realized that Chinese were one
of the earliest nations in the world to discover music.
</P>
<P>
Older than most European treasures on display in the Louvre
Museum, the chime bells can even today produce any cosmopolitan
and modern tunes from every country of the world.
</P>
<P>
The two concerts given by the China Chime-Bell Orchestra from
Hubei Province in central China have caused a real sensation among
their French listeners.
</P>
<P>
Most of the listeners discovered for the first time such a set
of ancient music instruments can play in concert with other modern
Chinese music instruments, such as flutes, pipa and eulhou.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ballet given by the dancers from Dance Institute of
Beijing has also been a great success.
</P>
<P>
Combining ancient themes with modern dancing techniques, the
artists showed the French a panorama of Chinese dances ranging
from the Dun Huang Silk Road Murals to the folk peasants of the
Loess Plateau border the Yellow River, the cradle of Chinese
civilization.
</P>
<P>
They also let their audience enjoy the Chinese version of
Shakespeare's ``Romeo and Juliette'' -- ``The Liang Zhu'' love
tragedy, with symbolic dancing language familiar to Europeans.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Opera is the field widely revisited by the French
this time, because of its fame abroad and its gorgeous masks and
costumes.
</P>
<P>
Behind a real Beijing Opera stage constructed in the exhibition
hall of UNESCO, a dressing table on which the actors and actresses
make up their faces with heavy color sticks has become the focus
of attention.
</P>
<P>
Some children have their faces painted like the Monkey King, a
story their fathers and grand fathers already knew thanks to a
successful tour of a Beijing Opera troupe in France in 1956. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
