<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uruguay Calls Back Ambassador in Paraguay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Uruguay's government Monday
called back its ambassador in Paraguay, Rodofo Olavarria, in the
diplomatic tension arising between both nations.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay's Foreign Minister Didier Opertti rejected before the
press the notion that Ambassador Olavarria's summons is a matter
of the eventual break of relations.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between both countries worsened after Uruguay denied
last week the extradition of Paraguay's Defense Minister Jose
Segovia.
</P>
<P>
Paraguay's government called for consultation for an indefinite
period of time its ambassadors in Uruguay, Julia Velilla, and in
Argentina, Leila Rachid.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, Argentina also rejected Paraguay's request of
extradition of ex-chief of the army Lino Cesar Oviedo.
</P>
<P>
Segovia went into exile on April 29 in Uruguay and Oviedo on
March 28 in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Paraguay's authorities alleged Segovia and Oviedo as
instigators of Vice President Luis Maria Aragna's killing on March
23 of last year. Oviedo is furthermore accused of heading a
proposed coup d'etat in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Paraguayan government recalled for an indefinite period of
time its ambassadors to Uruguay and Argentina last Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
