<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congolese Rebel Leader Disapproves New Army Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The second rebel leader
of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) Monday voiced
misgivings about the new army chief as the fledgling peace process
in the war-torn central African country got underway.
</P>
<P>
"General Sylvestre Luesha is very close to (DRC President)
Laurent Kabila. He is more of a Mai Mai organizer than a military
man," South African Press Association quoted Ernest Wamba dia
Wamba, head of the Goma faction of the Congolese Rally for
Democracy (RCD), as saying in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Kabila announced Luesha's appointment as new head of the DRC
armed forces on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wamba, who held talks with President Thabo Mbeki on Sunday,
said he would not go as far as the Kisangani RCD faction to demand
the removal of Luesha to avoid a resumption of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
"Although I have reservations about the general's competence, I
am not an advisor to Mr. Kabila to tell him whom he should appoint
and whom not. His government is in any event an outgoing one."
</P>
<P>
Chief negotiator for the Kisangani RCD faction Bazima Karaha
earlier in the day said Luesha's appointment was a violation of a
recent peace accord to end the DRC civil war.
</P>
<P>
"It is a threat. It is a violation. This man must be disarmed,"
Karaha said.
</P>
<P>
Karaha's objections stemmed from Luesha's close ethnic links
with the Mai Mai, one of the groups meant to be disarmed under the
peace deal, including a cease-fire, brokered in Lusaka. The Mai
Mai has clashed with the rebels in the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Wamba earlier told reporters he was optimistic that the
cease-fire would succeed in bringing an end to the year-long
conflict in the former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The challenge was to make sure that hostilities between
political adversaries also came to an end, Wamba said.
</P>
<P>
Wamba on Monday described the RCD's endorsement of the peace
accord as a great event, and expressed the hope that small
problems would not be allowed to derail the process.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the Joint Military Commission, which is
overseeing the cease-fire, went without a hitch. Only the number
of representatives each group should have still had to be sorted
out, Wamba said.
</P>
<P>
The accord calls for a cease-fire, the creation of a united
army after a 90-day dialogue on the DRC's political future, and
for international peacekeepers to monitor compliance.
</P>
<P>
Wamba said he hoped South Africa would continue to play a
central role in the process.
</P>
<P>
"The emphasis in the DRC has shifted from fighting to
negotiation, an area in which South Africa has rich experience. We
expect South Africa will do what it can in terms of resources,
expertise and maybe personnel," Wamba said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
