<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana to Lift State of Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Botswanan President
Festus Mogae is to end the four-day state of emergency on Tuesday
when he signs into law an amendment to include about 60,000
registered voters on the voters' roll, a presidential spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency, which was declared last Thursday, was
for the sole purpose of being able to recall the parliament to
amend the act, under which the aforementioned voters could not be
included on the roll because of a writ issued for the October 16
election before their names were published for inspection.
</P>
<P>
The parliament met Monday and made the changes, reports
reaching here quoted the unnamed spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
There has been widespread apathy ahead of the election in the
diamond- rich country and only about 400,000 out of 900,000
eligible voters initially registered.
</P>
<P>
Another 60,000 voters signed up in a supplementary registration
period.
</P>
<P>
Their inclusion on the roll will mean that 51 percent of
eligible voters have registered for the election.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition party, Botswana Congress Party, has been
accusing Mogae and the electoral commission of incompetence.
</P>
<P>
"While we appreciate that the (60,000) people must vote, we are
 concerned about the state of emergency that was imposed," said
party leader Michael Dingake.
</P>
<P>
"The state of emergency was unprecedented and it shows lack of
consideration, carelessness and negligence on the part of the
president," he charged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
