<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mitchell Trying to Break Stalemate in N.Irish Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. mediator George Mitchell
held a day of meetings Monday with the main rival parties in
Northern Ireland at the start of a review of the Good Friday
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell arrived in Northern Ireland at mid-night Sunday,
trying to revive the peace process after it reached a deadlock two
months ago over the disarmament of Catholic and Protestant
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell, who helped mediate last year's peace accord for the
British province, has been called in by Britain and the Irish
Republic.
</P>
<P>
"Neither I nor anyone else has a magic and that will wave away
these problems. But I believe it can be done. Whether it is done
is up to the political leaders," the former U.S. senator told
reporters before the meetings.
</P>
<P>
At the heart of the problem is an ambiguity in the peace deal
about disarmament which set May 2000 as the deadline but gave no
starting date for the process.
</P>
<P>
There was no sign of an easing of the mutual suspicion that
clouds hopes of implementing the April 1998 peace pact.
</P>
<P>
The province's main Protestant leader David Trimble still
insists that Sinn Fein should be barred from government until its
Irish Republican Army guerrilla allies disarm. The IRA is as
attached to its weapons as ever.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein official Pat Doherty said the review could be
successful, but it should conclude that the executive be set up
immediately.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell is due to meet smaller parties Tuesday and the British
and Irish governments Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On Monday he also met the other two parties with seats on the
planned executive -- the moderate SDLP, the main Catholic party,
which supports the peace deal, and Ian Paisley's Democratic
Unionists, who fiercely oppose it.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell stressed that his review would focus strictly on
devolving power and on achieving disarmament by May 2000.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell will take a break after Wednesday pending publication
of a report on reform of Northern Ireland's police force.
</P>
<P>
No finishing date has been set for Mitchell's talks, which will
reopen next Monday, but participants want them over soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
