<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Blue Chips End in Black </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 6 (Xinhua) - London's stock market ended in
the black Monday after a strong rally by US stocks on previous
session and positive gains from telecom stocks.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 closed up 43.6 points at 6375.7 on provisional
volume of 676m shares and the FTSE 250 rose 50.8 points, or 0.8
percent, to a record 6173.2.
</P>
<P>
Vodafone Airtouch was behind the bulk of gains on the UK blue
chip index. The stock closed 3.6 percent higher after the world's
largest cellular network operator confirmed it is talking to Bell
Atlantic about linking up their US mobile networks.
</P>
<P>
Rival Orange also made strong gains to finish 2.2 percent
higher. UK cable operator Telewest soared more than 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The major corporate development of the day was confirmation of
the 17.2 billion US dollars takeover of insurer Legal &AMP; General by
NatWest Bank.
</P>
<P>
However, market reaction as muted after stocks in the sector
had rallied last week when the two companies confirmed they were
in talks.
</P>
<P>
Natwest closed 0.8 percent lower on the session amid fears the
company was overpaying for L&AMP;G, which dropped 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The electronic Xetra Dax in Frankfurt put in the strongest
performance of the main bourses in Europe, closing 1.2 percent
higher at 5400.55, a rise of 64 points.
</P>
<P>
Paris's CAC 40 ended down 4 points at 4668.04, shedding the
mild gains it had held on to for most of the session. Retail and
automotive stocks led the way down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
