<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses U.S. Envoy of Blocking Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Trade Ministry on
Tuesday accused the U.S. representative at the U.N. Sanctions
Committee of hindering approval of its electrical contracts
signed under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the ministry told the Iraqi News Agency that
the blocked contracts with Spanish, French and German companies
involved equipments and spare parts for the electrical sector.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed spokesman said the continued U.S. impediment of
approval of Iraq's contracts reflects the U.S. administration's
hostile trend toward Iraq and its efforts to harm Iraqi people who
have been suffering under the nine-year-old U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal, now in its sixth phase, Iraq is
allowed to export limited amount of oil in every six months to buy
food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies for its 24 million
people.
</P>
<P>
Since the fourth phase of the deal, the ceiling of the amount
of oil Iraq is allowed to sell has been raised to 5.2 billion
U.S. dollars from 2 billion dollars in previous phases.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has long accused the U.S. and British envoys at the
Sanctions Committee of hampering the endorsement of its
contracts, arguing that the oil-for-food deal has failed to
alleviate the suffering of the Iraqi people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
