<HEADLINE> Japan, Thailand Agree to Enhance Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Japan and Thailand Tuesday
agreed to beef up trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was contained in a joint statement issued after
the seventh round of bilateral economic consultations held in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Japanese State Foreign Secretary Nobutaka Machimura and Thai
Deputy Foreign Minister Sukhumbhand Pribatra co-chaired the one-
day meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Welcoming the fact that the two economies have shown clear
signs of recovery, both sides engaged in a policy dialogue on
various issues of mutual interest,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides shared the view that such cooperation would be
helpful not only to the promotion of economic relations between
Japan and Thailand but also to the consolidation of the process of
the recovery and sustainable growth of the whole Asian region from
the economic crisis," it said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to set up a joint working group on food
quality improvement as a forum for private-sector cooperation and
to increase joint efforts in the development of Thailand's Mekong
River basin.
</P>
<P>
Japan has promised further support for Thailand's industrial
restructuring efforts. It will extend aid for Thailand's
developing industries and smaller businesses and will increase
technology transfers.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two countries will expand cooperation in
environmental issues on both bilateral and multilateral basis.
</P>
</TEXT>
