<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blind Chinese Benefit from Massive Eye Surgery Campaign (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A large-scale eye surgery
campaign will help China reduce the number of cataract sufferers,
as the disease now deprives some 400,000 Chinese of their sight
each year, making China the country with largest blind population
in the world.
</P>
<P>
SightFirst China Action (SFCA), which is described as the world
's biggest blindness prevention and treatment campaign, has helped
nearly one million people with cataracts and other eye diseases
regain their sight, it was announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Ministry of Health, the China Disabled Persons
Federation, and Lions Clubs International, who jointly launched
the SFCA program in 1997, told the press that the five-year
program is being carried out smoothly and has so far yielded
noticeable results.
</P>
<P>
Out of nine million eye patients in China, four millions have
cataracts. This condition, which is mainly associated with
increased age, has become rampant as a result of the increasing
population of the elderly in China.
</P>
<P>
Health experts warn that if the country's eye-surgery capacity
is limited to only 200,000 operations a year, that, along with a
regional imbalance in ophthalmologic services, will make the task
of overcoming cataracts almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
However, the SFCA program will help raise the country's surgery
capacity to 450,000 operations annually, which will in turn bring
down the number of cataract patients gradually by the year 2001,
said Vice Minister of Health Wang Longde.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, 92 medical teams were sent to 761 remote,
underdeveloped and poor counties to offer them operations at
greatly reduced fees, Wang told the press.
</P>
<P>
"Among those who regained their eyesight, the oldest was 103
and the youngest was only four months old," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blind Chinese Benefit from Massive Eye Surgery Campaign (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a bid to achieve the final goal of performing 1.75 million
operations in five years, the SFCA program has dispatched 250
medical teams while focusing on the establishment of new
ophthalmologic departments at local hospitals, training programs
for rural ophthalmologists and assistants, and expanded health
awareness among the population.
</P>
<P>
"About 6,000 eye doctors and assistants in rural areas have
received training and ophthalmologic departments have been opened
in 36 counties in 20 provinces since 1997," Wang said, adding that
a recently established national database network for the
prevention and treatment of eye diseases is the world's first.
</P>
<P>
The massive program will cost a total of 180 million U.S.
dollars, with over 15 million dollars provided by Lions Clubs
International and the rest coming from the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
James Ervin, president of Lions Clubs International, said that
so far the program results have been "truly remarkable," and that
the SFCA could be used as a model by other countries.
</P>
<P>
"Since its inception in 1997, SightFirst China Action has been
a flagship initiative with the SightFirst program," stressed
Ervin, who led other members of the organization at a meeting of
the SFCA Steering Committee and the ongoing Sixth General Assembly
of the International Agency for the Prevention of Blindness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
