<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Orders Harsh Actions Against Rebels in Daghestan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin on Tuesday ordered "rapid and harsh" actions against armed
rebels in the southern republic of Daghestan.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin described the rebels as terrorists when he chaired
Russia's top security body in the Kremlin to discuss developments
in Daghestan, where armed forces and police units are fighting
Islamic extremists, presidential spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin said.
</P>
<P>
"A week ago there was confidence that the large-scale armed
operation against the international terrorists was over,"
Yakushkin quoted Yeltsin as saying. "But the bandits have
undertaken new sorties and are organizing barbaric acts of
sabotage."
</P>
<P>
The Russian authorities have accused foreign forces of
supporting the armed incursions in the Caucasus republics.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin urged troops and police to act "quickly and harshly,"
the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Yeltsin blamed "careless" generals for
allowing a devastating car bomb attack on a Russian military
apartment block and the loss of an entire district of Daghestan to
Islamic rebels.
</P>
<P>
The blast, which demolished a five-story apartment in the town
of Buinaksk in a southern region of Daghestan Saturday, has left
64 people dead.
</P>
<P>
Hours after the blast, hundreds of Islamic militants invaded
Daghestan from neighboring Chechnya and seized several villages.
Russian forces, facing their toughest security challenge since the
1994-96 Chechnya war, are still trying to repel the incursion.
</P>
<P>
Interior Ministry officials estimated that around 1,000 Muslim
rebels have crossed into the Novolaksk region of western Daghestan
on Russia's southern rim and seized six villages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
