<HEADLINE> IAAF Insists Sydney Olympics Athletics Timetable "Not Valid" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Amateur
Athletics Federation (IAAF) insisted on Tuesday that the athletics
timetable for the 2000 Sydney Olympic Games "was not valid" and is
subject to change.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF said at Monte Carlo that the timetable had not been
approved in accordance with the Olympic Charter before the Sydney
organizing committee (SOCOG) released tickets to the public.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF said "the best interests of the athletes and their
health" must be considered before the timetable is finalized
though they "understands the frustration this will provoke among
the Australian people".
</P>
<P>
"Such a motivation could certainly not be considered any less a
priority than selling tickets," the IAAF said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
SOCOG members criticized the IAAF last weekend, saying that
they could throw the athletics timebatle into turmoil by asking
for amendments to the published schedule.
</P>
<P>
But the IAAF said it had advised SOCOG that no timetable should
be made public until it had been agreed. 
</P>
