<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Points of Agreement Between FIFA and AFC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Federation Internationale
de Football Association (FIFA) and the Asian Football
Confederation (AFC) have reached the agreement on the allocation
of places in the 2002 World Cup, according to a FIFA press
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed by FIFA President Sepp Blatter and
AFC President Sultan Ahmad Shah at FIFA headquarters in the Swiss
city of Zurich, Asia will have half the slot from UEFA made
possible by the efforts of the FIFA president and the UEFA
president, this making the Asian allocation to 4.5, including the
two host associations.
</P>
<P>
FIFA in cooperation with the confederations concerned will
decide on the play-off status for 2002 before the draw in December
1999. The FIFA president will then propose to the FIFA Executive
Committee to decide before the kick-off of the 2002 World Cup
Preliminary Competition, the seats for the different
confederations for the FIFA World Cup 2006.
</P>
<P>
The above-mentioned proposals will be submitted to the FIFA
Executive Committee at the meeting on October 1 and 2 in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
In view of the above, the AFC has decided to cancel the AFC
Extraordinary Congress which was scheduled for October 10 in Kuala
Lumpur. Furthermore, the member associations affiliated to the AFC
have been requested to submit their entry to FIFA to participate
in the FIFA World Cup South Korea/Japan 2002.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA said that the agreement was made after the AFC has
expressed its regrets regarding the walk-out of the Asian
delegates from the FIFA Extraordinary Congress on July 9 in Los
Angels.
</P>
<P>
"Unity in football has been restored and remains our priority
objective in the future," Blatter said. "We can look forward to
the FIFA World Cup in Japan and South Korea being a resounding
success."
</P>
<P>
AFC President Sultan Shah said, "I am happy to have been able
to resolve the differences between FIFA and my confederation
regarding the number of seats for the 2002 finals."
</P>
<P>
"Now we can move forward together for the good of the game in
Asia, and devote our full attention to the success of the World
Cup, which will be held in our continent for the first time at the
start of the new millennium," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
