<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts Urged to Intensify IP Education in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Intellectual
Property Department (IPD) Tuesday urged more efforts to strengthen
education in intellectual property in Hong Kong, following a
survey featuring residents' lower awareness on the work.
</P>
<P>
Conducted by the Hong Kong Institute of Asia-Pacific Studies of
the Chinese University of Hong Kong, the recent survey showed that
most of the respondents had a relatively little knowledge of the
works of the IPD and the Intellectual Property Investigation
Bureau of the Customs and Excise department.
</P>
<P>
"The general awareness of intellectual property among
respondents was far from inadequate, but a relatively high
percentage of people said they did not know what intellectual
property referred to, or held mis-conceptions about it," said
Stephen Selby, director of the IPD.
</P>
<P>
Respondents agreed that it is immoral for a consumer who knows
that it will infringe the intellectual property rights of others
to buy counterfeit or pirated articles. Yet, they admitted that
they themselves have also engaged in these activities, Selby said.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that the public in Hong Kong believe
that heavier punishment, more effort on combating trademark
counterfeiting and copyright piracy and more education are the
solutions to deal with intellectual property rights infringement.
</P>
<P>
The foundings of the survey will set the benchmark for IPD to
formulate its forth-coming promotion and education programs, Selby
said, adding that the department will spend eight million HK
dollars over the next three years on intellectual property
education and promotion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
