<HEADLINE> Greece's Inflation Drops to 2.0 Percent in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Greece's inflation fell from
2.1 percent in July to 2.0 percent in August, the National
Statistics Service (NSS) announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing this, the NSS said that the real inflation in August
was 1.98 percent, the lowest rate in Greece since February 1970.
</P>
<P>
The NSS said that the recent measures taken by the Greek
government to curb price inflation would result in a 0.6 percent
drop on year-on-year inflation.
</P>
<P>
A drop in the consumer price index in August reflected a fall
in food and non-alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
Greek Economy Minister Yiannos Papantoniou forecasted that the
inflation would continue falling.
</P>
<P>
Greece, which is the only country of EU members failing to join
the the euro zone, needs to hold inflation below 2 percent to
qualify for entry into the singly-currency euro zone by 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
