<HEADLINE> China to Open Wider to Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- China will open some ten
sectors more widely to overseas investment, including finance and
insurance and telecommunications, a senior Chinese official
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Restrictions on the number of overseas-funded insurers and
their locations will gradually be eased, said Wen Zaixing,
spokesman for the 3rd China Investment and Trade Fair which opens
tomorrow in Xiamen in east China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Overseas insurers will also be allowed to provide a wider
variety of services and hold larger shares in joint ventures, Wen
added.
</P>
<P>
China's telecommunications sector will first experiment with
overseas investment in its value-added business, and then open the
market to overseas capital step by step, Wen said.
</P>
<P>
More Chinese airlines will be encouraged to use overseas funds
and cooperate with overseas counterparts in establishing
engineering subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
The business scope for overseas-funded investment companies in
China will be enlarged, Wen said. For example, they will be
allowed to sell products made by their plants in China and open
research and development centers.
</P>
<P>
According to Wen, China will also extend its experiment with
overseas investment in areas such as accounting, assessment,
quality control and management, and legal counseling.
</P>
<P>
Wen also revealed plans to further open commerce, foreign trade,
tourism, and several other sectors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
