<HEADLINE> Lebanese Doctors to Stage Strike in Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's doctors will stage a
nation-wide strike Wednesday to protest against a verdict by a
Beirut military court that sentenced three doctors for negligence.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Lebanon's Medical Syndicate called on all
doctors in the country to stop work on Wednesday and deal only
with urgent cases.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of physicians in white robe will picket the Lebanese
parliament in downtown Beirut to demand a legislation that
immunizes the medical profession against prosecution without
scientific evidence, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The military tribunal Tuesday night sentenced the three accused
doctors to five days in jail each for their negligence which led
to the death of an army sergeant.
</P>
<P>
Since the three doctors had spent more than one week in custody
during the investigation, they were released after the trial.
</P>
<P>
The trial was the first of its kind in Lebanon's military court
history because the country does not have laws that pertain
specifically to medical malpractice and dissatisfied patients or
their families usually have to resort to the civil courts.
</P>
<P>
The case sparked strong protest and criticism from the
country's medical associations.
</P>
<P>
Ghattas Khouryt, the head of Medical Syndicate for Beirut and
North Lebanon, said "we are not against doctors facing up to their
responsibilities, but we do not accept that they be treated like
criminals."
</P>
<P>
"We are against their arrest, because we know this will create a
crisis between doctors and patients," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0084 </DOCNO>
