<HEADLINE> Philippines to Hold Consultation on Charter Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has ordered starting public consultations nationwide on
his proposal to amend the constitution in a bid to determine
people's true sentiments on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a recent cabinet meeting, Estrada voiced his
willingness to listen to public ideas on the issue, the Philippine
News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Preparatory Commission on charter change is charged with
collecting the results of the public consultation, according to
the president.
</P>
<P>
"I have instructed the commission to conduct wide-ranging
consultations to determine the true feelings of all sectors of the
society on the issue. I am ready to abide by the results after a
thorough study," he said at the cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the economic reforms proposed in the charter
change, which aim to relax the constitutional restrictions on the
entry of foreign capital into the country, are vital to the
economy's survival under a rapidly changing world order.
</P>
<P>
The Constitution bars foreigners from owning land and gaining a
 controlling stake in local business ventures.
</P>
<P>
"The aim of our proposals is to remove the barriers that hold
back our economy as the rest of the world races to the new
millennium," Estrada stressed. 
</P>
