<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archaeologist Couple Trace Chinese History in Ancient Tombs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Since Liu Qingzhu and Li
Yufang married 30 years ago, they have spent most of their time
digging in ancient old gloomy tombs and searching through desolate
ruins.
</P>
<P>
The couple are well-known Chinese archaeologists now in their
50's who have specialized in studying tombs of Chinese emperors
and ancient cities, and are credited with discovering China's
earliest central archives, from the Western Han Dynasty (206 BC -
24 AD).
</P>
<P>
"At the turn of the century, people are asking themselves '
Where do we go from here?' To answer that question, we have to
trace our history, and make it clear where we came from," said Liu
Qingzhu, director of the Institute of Archaeology under the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"The 50 years since the founding of New China is only a flash
in the history of the human race, but these years have brought
qualitative changes to China," said the archaeologist, adding that
these changes have been greater than those in all of the 2,000
years of Chinese feudal history.
</P>
<P>
After the couple graduated from the Department of Archaeology
of the prestigious Beijing University in 1967, they were drawn
ever closer together by archaeology.
</P>
<P>
Their thought always lingered in the tombs of the Qin and Han
dynasties of more than 2,000 years ago, and through the years,
many ancient swords, jade pieces, coins, and tiles and bricks
which were buried in oblivion came to light, thanks to the efforts
of the couple.
</P>
<P>
Liu recalled that when China's archaeological research resumed
in 1973 after a halt during the so-called Cultural Revolution, he
took part in the excavation of the palace of Qin Shihuang, the
first emperor of the Qin Dynasty (221- 206 BC) near Xi'an in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
"Every day I rode my bicycle for more than 50 kilometers to the
site, and walked through the high wild grass. I felt excited." Liu
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
