<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archaeologist Couple Trace Chinese History in Ancient Tombs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li recalled the excavation of a tomb of the Western Han Dynasty.
"As I was cleaning the wall, suddenly the wheel barrow carrying
earth to the outside of the tomb broke and came rushing at me. I
stepped aside in time and fortunately escaped the barrow."
</P>
<P>
At the site, where Li had her narrow escape, nearly 60,000
pieces of bones inscribed with Chinese characters were discovered.
These bones later proved to be China's earliest central archive.
</P>
<P>
The excavation report written by the couple titled "A Study of
the Emperors' Tombs of the Qin and Han Dynasties" is the most
detailed monograph about the subject and has been translated into
Japanese.
</P>
<P>
The five decades since the founding of New China is an era full
of surprising discoveries for Chinese archaeologists, giving them
the opportunity to recover the traces of ancient culture.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, there were more than 500 excavation sites in
China every year, as Chinese archaeologists experienced the
romance and glory of discovery during this era.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archaeologist Couple Trace Chinese History in Ancient Tombs (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The work of Liu and Li during that decade was substantially
more than other archaeologists, as they spent at least ten months
of every year excavating and researching in the field.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years, they have taken part in the excavation
of the ancient city of Yueyang, and Xianyang, the capital of the
Qin Dynasty, and the tombs and capital of the Han Dynasty. They
also investigated the 11 tombs of the Han Dynasty and 18
mausoleums of the Tang Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
"As we see the results of the our work, the hardship and pains
are totally forgotten," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
"Archaeological excavation is extremely hard for women, but
patience and care are to my advantage," said Li, who was named one
of 100 heroines in Chinese governmental departments this year.
</P>
<P>
Liu, honored as a correspondent academician of the Deutcher
Archaeological Institute, said that conditions for archaeological
excavation have been greatly improved, and they are now equipped
with cars, notebook computers and mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
In the eyes of the archaeologist, tools are the most important
artifacts representing social development. "From the Stone Age to
the Bronze Age, from the Iron Age to the ages of the steam engine
and computer, the improvement of tools has changed the world."
</P>
<P>
Liu and Li said they hope to help make Chinese proud of their
splendid culture. "Unveiling the past tells us the future. Chinese
people are able to advance to the forefront of the world, because
our ancestors ever walked at the forefront."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
