<HEADLINE> Taiwan Businessman Refutes Lee Teng-hui's Separatist Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A Taiwan businessman with
investments in inland areas wrote a letter to leading Chinese
newspaper People's Daily some days ago saying that Lee Teng-hui's
"two states" remarks seriously hurt the feelings and damaged the
interests of all Chinese, including the people of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan compatriot said in his letter that Lee made the
separatist remarks without regarding the Taiwan people's desire
for stability, peace and improvement of cross-Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
He said, "As a businessman who has been investing in inland
areas for 11 years and a Chinese with national feelings, I was
shocked by Lee's remarks."
</P>
<P>
He said he strongly opposes Lee's splittist remarks and
believes that most peace-loving Taiwan people welcome the sound
development of cross-Straits economic, trade and cultural
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The businessman added that most Taiwan people are looking
forward to the visit to Taiwan this autumn of Wang Daohan, head of
the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits, and
expecting that it will push ahead cross-Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
He said the "two-states" remarks and the idea of "Taiwan
Independence" are the political plot of a small number of people
in Taiwan with ulterior motives, and do not represent the will of
the people of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The businessman said that as a native of Taiwan, he has been
focusing his investment in inland areas since the two sides of the
Taiwan Straits began economic and trade exchanges.
</P>
<P>
His ventures have grown from a small processing factory for
imported materials to a multinational corporation.
</P>
<P>
He said the opening policy of the inland areas and cross-
Straits exchanges have brought him great opportunities and much
benefit.
</P>
<P>
He said business people with investments in inland areas are
expecting early reunification of the motherland and prosperity for
the entire Chinese nation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
