<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Charter Change Enhances Economic Nationalism: Philippine Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The proposal to introduce
economic reforms through charter change will enhance, instead of
violate, the principle of "economic nationalism," Philippine
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The official made this clear as he stressed the need for a new
approach to achieve economic nationalism in response to changing
economic realities, the Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said, "what will be changed is the method or the approach to
attain this objective. What we want to change is the method."
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada is presently pushing
economic reforms through the charter change to remove the
constitutional barriers that slow down economic growth and prevent
the country from catching up with its more progressive neighbors
in the region.
</P>
<P>
These reforms include relaxing the restrictions on the foreign
ownership of land and local businesses, including public
utilities.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said economic nationalism is as important a principle
in the ongoing charter change process as it is in the present
constitution.
</P>
<P>
He added that the issue of the control of ownership being
transferred to foreigners, which some critics are protesting, is
merely a method to attain the new concept of economic nationalism
under a borderless trade environment.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu quoted Estrada as saying that the new nationalism
means bringing in the foreign capital needed to sharpen the global
competitiveness of domestic industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
