<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Envoy Visits Syria on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouq El-Sharaa discussed the European role in the Mideast peace
process and the Syrian-EU ties with European Union (EU) Special
Envoy to the Middle East Angle Mauratinus on Tuesday .
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Mauratinus, who arrived here earlier in the
day, said the talks dealt with the peace process on the Syrian
track in view of a recent visit by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to the region.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reviewed the revised agreement for the Wye
Accord, or the Sharm El-Sheikh memorandum, signed Sunday between
Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Israel begins to pull its troops from
another 11 percent of the West Bank within 10 days and completes
the process by January 20 next year. And the long-overdue final
status talks will start on September 13.
</P>
<P>
Mauratinus pointed out that he will continue the joint efforts
with the Syrian and U.S. officials to resume the peace talks on
the Syrian track, which have been stalled since early 1996.
</P>
<P>
Damascus welcomes the European role to push forward the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Criticizing the Sharm El-Sheikh deal, Syria questioned the
seriousness of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in making a
substantial progress in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sharaa has expressed disappointment after meeting with
Albright because she failed to bring Israeli assurances which
Syria seeks as a basis for resuming talks. Syria wants the talks
to be resumed from where they were left off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
