<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Develops Gadget to Translate Texts Into Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Indian scientists have
developed a hi-tech gadget which scans printed characters of two
of the most popular Indian scripts, corrects all errors and
automatically translates the written text into speech.
</P>
<P>
The first bi-script, bilingual Optical Character Recognition
(OCR) system of its kind developed in the country, is capable of
working effectively on Bengali and Devnagari scripts, according to
the Press Trust of India.
</P>
<P>
Envisioned by a team of four computer wizards headed by Dr.
Umapada Pal of the Indian Statistical Institute based in Calcutta,
the OCR system is expected to be of immense help for the blind,
who can now "hear" any printed text in these two languages.
</P>
<P>
The system is expected to be cleared by the institute in June
2000 and will be commercialized after that. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
