<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Kuwait Defense Ministers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Defense Minister Chi
Haotian held talks here today with visiting Kuwait Deputy Prime
Minister and Defense Minister Sheikh Salem Sabah Al-Salem Al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
Chi, also vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission and
a state councilor, said that China and Kuwait are both developing
countries, share the same interests and hold a consensus on major
international issues.
</P>
<P>
Chi voiced his appreciation of the Kuwait government's
adherence to the "One-China" policy and its support for China on
such issues as human rights.
</P>
<P>
"Recent years have witnessed fine progress in military
relations between both countries," Chi said, adding that the
Chinese army hopes to increase exchange and cooperation with the
Kuwait armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Chi also reiterated China's consistent stand toward the
remaining issues of the Gulf War and the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Al-Salem made assurances that the Kuwait government will
continue to stick to the "One-China" policy. The successful
running of Hong Kong after its return to the motherland has spoken
for the success of the policy of "One Country, Two Systems", he
commented, adding that Kuwait hopes that Macao will also return to
the motherland at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Al-Salem also expressed his wish of further enhancing ties with
China. "We hope that China will play greater role in international
affairs, particularly in the Middle East peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait guests are here for a 10 day official visit to China
at the invitation of Chi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
