<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Fruit Exporters Urged to Register for Licenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Exporters of durian, longan
and orchid in Thailand were urged to register for export licenses
and be ready for all relevant information printed on their
packaging, the Thai News Agency (TNA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Customs Department has set September 10 as the deadline to
get tough with the export, TNA quoted a senior official from the
Agriculture and Cooperatives Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ananta Dalodom, chief of the Agriculture Department, said some
100 exporters have registered for licenses to date, most of which
are orchid exporters, followed by durian exporters.
</P>
<P>
Longan exporters are permitted to use the existing licenses
they have registered with the Export Promotion Department as a
relaxation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation by the Customs Department is part of its
efforts to help the shipment of fruits as customs officials will
not unseal packaging for inspection again if such goods have
licenses issued by the Agriculture Department, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The registration and information printed on the packaging will
also help the Agriculture Department trace back where the goods
are from and when the buying countries rejected their products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
