<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Security Adviser in London for Looted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Vice-President Atiku
Abubakar disclosed Monday that his government has dispatched its
National Security Adviser to London to try to retrieve some of the
country's stolen money stashed in foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president said that he did not know the total amount
expected to be retrieved until the money was finally in the
government's vault, the government-run Daily Times newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"When we came in, we found out that the immediate past
administration conducted a lot of investigation into corrupt
practices with a view to first of all recovering the loot," said
Abubakar
</P>
<P>
"They have done a pretty good job and we are continuing from
where they stopped. I have been personally involved in
negotiations to recover some of this loot and we have made
progress. We have made a number of recoveries which we will
announce shortly, " he said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the National Security Adviser Mohammed Gusau has gone
to London for the issue, said the vice-president.
</P>
<P>
"It is when you make these recoveries that you take a decision
whether it is worthwhile to go to court as part of the terms of
the recovery," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise, if you just try and say 'look, what we are after is
the punitive aspect of the thing', you may never recover any penny
and really succeed in prosecuting because that is much more public
and difficult to prove," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president asked the press to practice patient and
allow the government to conclude the recovery process before
talking about prosecution of those involved in the looting.
</P>
</TEXT>
