<HEADLINE> Nigerian Govt. Promises 5 Million New Jobs for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Five million jobs are to be
created in the next year while about 5,000 housing units are to be
built yearly among other goals to be reached in the next four
years, Nigerian Vice- President Atiku Abubakar has said
</P>
<P>
Taking stock of the Olusegun Obasanjo administration's 100 days
in office at a press briefing in Abuja Monday, the vice-president
said that the Federal Government has released 100 million naira
(one U.S. dollar equals some 90 naira) as motor vehicle and
motorcycle revolving loan for officers and men of the Nigerian
police to combat rising crime in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspapers Tuesday quoted Abubakar as saying that
the administration was determined to create a conducive
environment for the generation of new employment opportunities
through private sector involvement.
</P>
<P>
"Plans are underway to generate five million jobs in the next
one year through vocational skills acquisition and entrepreneurs
development program in all the local government councils of the
federation," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the housing program, the vice president said the National
Housing Program would be revived soon, adding that "over the next
four years, the government intends to build 5,000 housing units
annually throughout the federation."
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the 410 housing units are in practical
completion stage and work has already commenced on the
construction of expandable one- and-two bedroom housing units in
Lugbe, Abuja and Lagos".
</P>
<P>
He said the issue of security of life and property was top on
the priority list of the administration.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Ministry of Police Affairs has finalized
a five- year development plan that would address the provision of
adequate security for citizens.
</P>
<P>
This included yearly recruitment and training, detailed
equipment handling for the recruited personnel and setting out
educational standards for new entrants into the force, he added.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president also disclosed that the Federal Ministry of
Works and Housing has revived the stalled highway projects
especially those under- funded or abandoned by past
administrations, such as Benin-Asaba dual carriage-way,
Otta-Abeokuta road, Kano Ring Road Phase II, Maiduguri-Dikwa-
Gamboru and Kano State border-Gumel-Maigatari road, among others.
</P>
</TEXT>
