<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Wants Internet Contents Regulated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Tuesday called
for a global consensus to regulate offensive contents in the
Internet to protect the public from their adverse effects.
</P>
<P>
No single country in the world could come up with its own
effort to tackle the problem which could damage the culture of
many countries especially developing ones like Malaysia, Energy,
Communications and Multimedia Minister Leo Moggie said here.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult unless a common understanding among countries
worldwide is reached on the need to restrain unwanted contents in
the Internet," he told reporters after opening the three-day 30th
Annual Conference of the International Institute of Communications
themed "The Knowledge Society - Commerce, Culture and Communities
in Development."
</P>
<P>
Moggie said the issue should be raised as often as possible in
international fora.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the Malaysian government has a duty to
protect the public from adverse contents in the Internet
especially the exposure of minors to pornography.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that in the context of the Multimedia Super
Corridor (MSC) where the government has guaranteed the free flow
of information, there would be no censorship on information posted
on the Internet and it would be accessible to everyone.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, Internet sales in Malaysia were
projected to grow from 46 million U.S. dollars this year to 1
billion dollars by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, the minister also called on developing
countries to work together to establish a common news network to
promote fair and accurate news reporting.
</P>
<P>
He said many of these countries do not have their own news
agencies and rely on the services of major news groups, thus
exposing them to negative reporting.
</P>
<P>
Moggie said many investment decisions were made on the basis of
news and reports published by major news organizations and as
such, commercialization together with an open market environment
had resulted in news being exploited mainly for economic benefits
and financial considerations.
</P>
<P>
To counter this monopoly on information communication
technologies and narrow the disparity between the
information-rich and information-poor countries, there is a need
for the developing countries to adopt technologies that are able
to provide equal access and empowerment for them, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
