<HEADLINE> Mahathir: Proposed EAEC in Better Position to Help Asian Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The East Asian Economic
Caucus (EAEC) proposed by Malaysia would be in a better position
to set up the proposed Asian Monetary Fund to help Asian countries
overcome their financial problems, Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The EAEC is better suited to take care of financial problems
faced by Asian countries, Mahathir told a news conference in the
eastern state of Pahang at the end of his two-day visit to the
state, Bernama news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said aid presently offered by the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) has a lot of strings attached.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir also said Japan could help the EAEC by giving loans or
investing directly to help the economies in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
He was of the view that when Japan helps the economies of East
Asia, East Asian countries will be a better market for Japan and
therefore what Japan invests in East Asia will actually help
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on calls for APEC (Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation) to act on the second speculative attack on the Thai
baht, Mahathir said, "I don't think APEC is capable of doing
anything about the currency situation. That is left to the big
powers, the Group of Seven."
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has called for formulating a new financial
architecture which will regulate currency trading.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir has announced that he will not attend the APEC
leaders' informal meeting in Auckland, New Zealand, later this
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
