<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The flow of direct foreign investments to Egypt has
increased from 200 million U.S. dollars in 1990 to 1 billion
dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's Arab daily Alam Al Yom quoted a report as saying that
Egypt and South Africa together absorb over 50 percent of the
total flow of investments to African states.
</P>
<P>
The report emphasized that the huge local market in Egypt
constitutes an important factor in attracting direct foreign
investments.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian Minister of Agriculture Hashem Shbul has
denied the existence of agricultural ties between Jordan and
Israel, pointing out that the two countries are currently engaged
in talks to put into effect agreements in the field of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's Alam Al Yom quotes Shbul as saying that agricultural
cooperation is directed towards Arab states.
</P>
<P>
He said Jordan is making contacts with Qatar and Saudi Arabia
in a bid to lift their ban on Jordanian agricultural and poultry
products, now that tests have proven that Jordan is completely free
of dioxine infections.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The annual petrochemical production potentials of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states are expected to reach some
41.5 million tons by the year 2003, as compared to their current
level of 19 million tons, with an annual rate of growth of 23
percent.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a study worked out by Gulf industrial investment
organisation, Tuesday's Alam Al Yom says the highest rate of
petrochemical production will be achieved by Qatar and the United
Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
During the period from 1998 to 2003, the annual rate of growth
in Qatar and UAE is due to reach about 152.8 percent and 116.4
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Total investments in joint petrochemical ventures in GCC states
during the period from 1998 to 2003 are estimated at 9.2 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The Iranian government approved Sunday an ambitious
five-year (2000/2005) economic plan which would provide about
750,000 job opportunities, though it would largely depend on
petroleum revenues.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's Arab daily Al Hayat quoted Deputy Chairman of the
Iranian Planning and Treasury Organisation Mohamed Ali Najafi as
saying that the plan stipulates the provision of 750,000 job
opportunities as well as an annual rate of growth of 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The plan is due to be submitted to the Consultative Council
next week for endorsement, he said.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Islamic Development Bank (IDB) Tuesday
decided to allocate 590 million dollars for new projects between
its member states and non-IDB members.
</P>
<P>
The funds were approved at the conclusion of the 187th
session of the Jeddah-based IDB, said a press release by the
bank, quoted by the Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Of the money, 300 million dollars will go for the
reconstruction of buildings and houses demolished in the recent
killer earthquakes in northwest Turkey, while some 50 million
dollars were granted to Turkey to build hospitals and schools,
the release said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the rest funds will be used to finance trade
operations.
</P>
<P>
The IDB, an affiliate with the Organization of the Islamic
Conference, was founded in 1974 to help push forward development
projects and promote inter-Islamic trade in the 53 member states.
</P>
<P>
The bank, with a capital of 9 billion dollars, has extended 20
billion dollars for over 2,450 development projects since it
started operations in 1976. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
