<HEADLINE> HK Works to Ensure Clean Election of District Councils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Independent Commission
Against Corruption (ICAC) of Hong Kong is organizing a series of
educational and publicity activities to ensure the District
Councils election in November is run in a clean and fair manner.
</P>
<P>
Announcing details of the Support Clean Elections activities,
ICAC's Director of Community Relations Rosanna Ure said Tuesday
that the activities aim to enhance public knowledge and
understanding of the Corrupt and Illegal Practices Ordinance (CIPO)
.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that candidates and their election agents
understand the law so that they would not breach it unknowingly,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
The ICAC, the Registration and Electoral Office and the Home
Affairs Department will jointly organize 18 briefings for all
candidates and their election agents to enhance their awareness
and understanding of the CIPO and electoral regulations.
</P>
<P>
Starting from Tuesday, the ICAC will operate an election
hotline to answer inquiries on aspects of the CIPO. Radio and TV
commercials, advertisements, posters and the Internet will also be
used to highlight the importance of clean elections.
</P>
<P>
Teresa Wu, chief investigator of the ICAC's Operations
Department, said the ICAC, the Registration and Electoral Office
and the Police had established a referral system to ensure that
different types of complaints in relation to the election would be
dealt with expeditiously.
</P>
<P>
Wendy Mark, group head of the Corruption Prevention Department,
said her department and the Constitutional Affairs Bureau will
regularly review the CIPO to plug any potential loopholes for
corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
