<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AFC Withdraws World Cup Boycott Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Asian Football
Confederation (AFC) formally withdrew its threatened boycott of
the 2002 World Cup finals on Tuesday after reaching an agreement
with FIFA on the allocation of teams for the finals.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement released here by AFC and FIFA,
following a meeting in Zurich, Asian teams would participate in
the tournament to be held in Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Asia's boycott threats were dropped after the AFC agreed to
accept a playoff berth offered by European governing body UEFA.
The berths for the Asian teams will remain as four and a half but
FIFA said in a statement it will reconsider the allocation of
Asian places for the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
"I am very happy about the outcome of this meeting with His
Royal Highness. Unity in football has been restored and remains
our priority objective in the future. We can look forward to the
FIFA World Cup in Japan and Korea being a resounding success,"
Sepp Blatter, FIFA chief said in a statement from Zurich released
through the Asian Football Confederation here.
</P>
<P>
AFC President Sultan Ahmad Shah said: "I am happy to have been
able to resolve the differences between FIFA and my Confederation
regarding the number of seats for the 2002 finals. Now we can move
forward together for the good of the game in Asia, and devote our
full attention to the success of the World Cup, which will be held
in our continent for the first time at the start of the new
millennium."
</P>
<P>
Asian members had subjected the boycott threat after being
handed only four berths at the tournament with a play-off chance
against a team from Europe. The four berths included the two co-
hosts Japan and South Korea. The AFC had demanded five automatic
berths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
