<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fixed-Asset Investment Boosts Growth of China's Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's Ministry of Finance has recently announced a 60-billion-
yuan (about 7.25 billion U.S. dollars) special bond issue to fund
spending on fixed assets to boost economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the move is necessary to consolidate and
continue the growing trend of the national economy, which rose a
7.6 percent in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China also issued an additional 100-billion-yuan
special bonds to prime-pump fixed-asset investment, which is
estimated to have pushed the growth of the national economy up by
1.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the National Bureau of Statistics indicate that
from 1950 to 1998, China spent a total 17.7993 trillion yuan on
fixed-asset construction, which laid a solid foundation for the
rapid growth of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 50 years, China has set up, from almost nothing,
a relatively comprehensive industrial complex, with its output of
iron and steel as well as coal currently ranking the first in the
world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fixed-Asset Investment Boosts Growth of China's Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Currently, the nation's annual output of crude oil stands at
160 million tons, ranking the fifth in the world, while its annual
power output has reached 1.167 trillion kwh, ranking second in
the world.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of a number of modern automobile works,
including the No.1 Automobile Works, No.2 Automobile Works and
Shanghai Volkswagen Corp., has greatly boosted China's auto
production capacity. China's auto output hit 1.63 million units in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the rapid development of traditional industries, new
industries such as electronics are also on a constant rise.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the output of micro-computers exceeded 2.9 million
units, and that of many home-appliances such as TV sets,
refrigerators and air-conditioners were also among the highest in
the world.
</P>
<P>
Fixed-asset investment has greatly boosted the construction of
water-conservancy facilities.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, China had built 85,000 large- and medium-
sized reservoirs, which can hold more than 450 billion cubic
meters of water.
</P>
<P>
And nearly 6,000 irrigation areas have been developed, with the
acreage of efficient irrigation surpassing 20 million hectares. (
more)
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fixed-Asset Investment Boosts Growth of China's Economy (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By the end of last year, the total transport system of the
country, including highways and railways, totaled 2.975 million
kilometers, 15.4 times the figure in 1949 when the New China was
founded.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the capacity of telephone exchanges reached 138
million lines, while the second largest mobile telecommunication
network in the world was set up.
</P>
<P>
From 1979 to 1997, China spent more than 3.24 trillion yuan on
housing construction, and 16.1 billion square meters of floor
space were completed, raising the per-capita livable space of
urban residents to 9.3 square meters in 1998 from 3.6 square
meters in 1978 and that of rural residents to 23.7 square meters
from 8.1 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 50 years, China's fixed-asset construction has
gone through various stages.
</P>
<P>
During the "First-Five-Year-Plan" period (1953-1957), China
spent 61.2 billion yuan in fixed assets, with which a batch of
basic industrial projects necessary for the country's
industrialization were completed.
</P>
<P>
In the following 20 years, fixed-asset investment experienced
ups and downs due to the "leftist" influence.
</P>
<P>
When reform and opening up policies were introduced in 1978,
China mapped out an economic development strategy focusing on
agriculture, energy, communications, education, and science and
technology, and fixed-asset investment enjoyed rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, fixed-asset investment has become a major factor
for boosting the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Last year, fixed-asset investment jumped 14.1 percent over the
previous year, contributing more than 60 percent to GDP and
accounting for 4.8 percentage points in the 7.8-percent economic
growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
