<HEADLINE> China's Early Rice Output Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- China's early rice output in
1999 reached 40.95 million tons, up 1.1 percent over 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Bureau of Statistics, the total
acreage of the crop this year dropped by 180,000 hectares, down 2.
3 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the unit output of early rice rose to 5,368 kg per
hectare, up 3.4 percent, due to relatively favorable weather
conditions and optimized production mix.
</P>
<P>
This year, the Chinese Government raised the purchasing price
for quality grain while abandoning the protection price for poor-
quality grain, a move that has prompted farmers to reduce the
acreage of poor-quality early rice.
</P>
<P>
Instead, farmers increased the acreage of quality early rice.
In central China's Hunan Province, for example, the acreage of
early rice acreage jumped more than 50 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Actively Pursues Int'l Cooperation to Combat Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese procuratorial bodies
are pushing for international cooperation in the fight against
corruption and have initiated global contacts as one important
step for stopping embezzlement and bribery, Chinese senior
prosecutor Zhao Dengju said here today.
</P>
<P>
China has signed bilateral treaties of judicial assistance
and extradition with more than 20 countries and are negotiating
such treaties with additional countries, said Zhao, deputy
procurator-general of the Supreme People's Procuratorate, at the
ongoing annual meeting of International Association of Prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
Such cooperation involves investigations, obtaining
evidence, freezing bank accounts, search and seizure, delivery of
litigation documents, and the arrest of criminal suspects, Zhao
said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese anti-corruption officials have effectively curbed
the spread of embezzlement and bribery through decades of effort,
but new developments in recent years have contributed to more
difficulties in the fight against such crimes, he said.
</P>
<P>
He listed these new developments as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- Modern financial settlement and operation methods have
changed the way bribery is carried out, and in many cases this
crime has become even more covert;
</P>
<P>
-- New cases perpetrated by making use of modern scientific
and technical knowledge, specifically electronic and special
knowledge about futures and securities are on the increase, which
is often difficult for prosecutors; and
</P>
<P>
-- Globalization of commerce also gives rise to
transnational crimes of bribery and embezzlement, and joint
efforts for cross-border assistance in combating such crimes still
lag behind, creating many difficulties for prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
Zhao urged prosecutors from all countries to join hands in
sharing their anti-corruption experience, circulating and
delivering anti-corruption information and data, and training.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
