<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Report: Suicides Cost Multi-Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Suicides can cost the society
multi-million dollars a year, according to a study published
Tuesday in Canada.
</P>
<P>
The country's Globe and Mail newspaper said that the average
cost of each suicide reached 849,877.80 Canadian dollars (about
569,424.29 U.S. dollars) in the eastern province of New Brunswick
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The total 96 suicide cases cost the society 80 million Canadian
dollars (about 53.6 million dollars) in the province that year,
the newspaper added.
</P>
<P>
The figures, billed as the first in Canada, were released in
the current issue of Chronic Diseases in Canada written by two
researchers Alberta Barcelo and Dale Clayton.
</P>
<P>
Suicides cause direct costs for health care services, autopsies,
funerals and police investigations, as well as indirect costs from
lost productivity and earnings, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Barcelo said in an interview that the study was done to
show the importance of measures to prevent suicide.
</P>
<P>
"Economic studies are a way to raise awareness of a health
problem. That way you can show people the importance of prevention
in that area," the newspaper quoted him as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
