<HEADLINE> Malaysia Hopes East Timor Ballot Result Accepted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia hopes that the
result of the ballot in East Timor will be accepted in good faith
by the parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
"We want the result to be accepted because the Indonesian
government decided to give the East Timor people a choice of
remaining within Indonesia as an autonomous region or being
independent. Now that they have chosen to be independent, the
parties concerned have to accept the result," Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir gave his view at a press conference at the end of his
two-day visit to the eastern state of Pahang, when asked to
comment on the latest developments in East Timor which had plunged
into disorder following the United Nations-organized ballot held
on August 30, Bernama news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. announced last Saturday that 78.5 percent of East
Timorese had opted for independence from Indonesia and rejected
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
News reports from Jakarta Tuesday said Indonesia had declared
martial law in East Timor by presidential decree following
continued rioting and killings in the territory. 
</P>
