<HEADLINE> Indonesian President: Martial law in E.Timor Temporary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie said here Tuesday that the state of military emergency
proclaimed in East Timor could be temporary, and could be revoked
if the situation returns to normal.
</P>
<P>
Habibie said peace and order could not be restored in the
territory if the violence continues.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Armed Forces declared a state of emergency in
East Timor Tuesday morning following serious violence occurred in
the territory after the announcement of the direct autonomy ballot
on September 4.
</P>
<P>
Reports said dozens of people have been killed in the clashes
between the pro-integration and pro-independence groups in the
last three days.
</P>
<P>
The clashes also forced more than 100,000 people to flee to
some provinces in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Habibie said the government will fulfill the responsibility of
maintaining security and carry through an orderly governmental
transition to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"The government respects and accepts the ballots' result that
78.5 percent of East Timorese voters have turned down Indonesia's
offer of autonomy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Habibie also called on all parties in East Timor to restrain
themselves and to end the bloodshed. Without having support from
all layers of society, it will be impossible to restore peace and
order, he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Defense Minister and Commander of the Armed Forces
Wiranto said the conditions will be worse if the state of
emergency is not proclaimed in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said the security situation remains tense, as brutal actions
such as killing and burning keep occurring. Economic activities
and public service are paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
On the presence of a U.N. peace-keeping force, Wiranto
reiterated that the government can get its own security forces to
restore law and order in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony annexed by Indonesia in
1976, has been seen by the United Nations as a non-self-governing
territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
