<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Signs Tax Treaty with Portugal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Singapore and Portugal
Tuesday signed an agreement on the avoidance of double taxation
and prevention of fiscal evasion with respect to taxes on income.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister for Finance Richard Hu and Portuguese
Minister of Finance Antonio Luciano Pacheco de Sousa Franco signed
the agreement on behalf of their respective governments.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which will enter into force after it has been
ratified by both countries, is the 42nd comprehensive tax treaty
which Singapore has signed.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will serve to prevent double taxation of income
earned in one country by a resident of the other and the document
will make clear the taxing rights between Singapore and Portugal
on all forms of income which arise as a consequence of
cross-border economic activities between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also provides for reduction or exemption of tax
at source on certain types of income.
</P>
<P>
These provisions are expected to bring about greater cross-flow
of trade, investment, technical know-how and expertise between the
two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
