<HEADLINE> Poor Students Offered Special Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- As a way of helping poor
college students complete their studies, China's Ministry of
Education has continued its 700 million-yuan loan scheme across
eight major cities, including Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The scheme was first introduced in 1994 and the ministry says
it has strived to perfect it ever since, even by issuing
instructions for education departments at all levels to make real
efforts to ensure students who are financially-strapped can
continue studying.
</P>
<P>
In June this year the ministry re-issued the memo, asking local
governments and universities to deduct ten percent of the tuition
fee as a help for students.
</P>
<P>
As a further help, Chinese universities have also set up a
system which incorporates fellowships, loans and other funds for
helping students, all of which have helped towards the goal of
ensuring every college student can complete their studies.
</P>
