<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Import Chinese Uniform Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will import school
uniform materials worth 10.2 million U.S. dollars from China under
an intergovernmental trade agreement, a senior Chinese diplomat
here confirmed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Education and Higher Education Ministry of Sri Lanka will
buy the 11.3 million meter-long materials for the year 2000 from
China at a concessionary price, said Dong Jiang, the first
secretary of the Chinese Embassy.
</P>
<P>
The ministry could save 210,000 dollars for the price is two
percent less than the usual price in response to a request made by
Minister Richard Pathirana, she said.
</P>
<P>
The two governments signed the agreement last Friday, Dong
said, adding that there is almost a 50 percent increase in trade
volumes on the uniform materials over last year.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka imported 7.8 million meters uniform material at a
cost of 6.89 million dollars from China in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government carries out a free education policy.
It spends more than 30 million dollars each year to provide free
uniform materials, textbooks and concessionary travel facilities
for students.
</P>
<P>
The distribution of free uniform materials was first initiated
in 1993. The new materials will be distributed among school
children within the first term of the year 2000. 
</P>
