<HEADLINE> Chinese Science Foundation Cracks Down On Cheats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A crackdown on scientists who
cheat when applying for research and other related funds is to be
strengthened in a bid to ensure that the system is not abused in
the future and used properly.
</P>
<P>
The campaign has been launched by the supervising committee of
the National Natural Science Foundation of China (NNSFC) and an
official said today that fraudulent practice will be strictly
punished.
</P>
<P>
Examples of such activities include a teacher at a university,
referred to only by his surname Xia, who has lost the right to
apply for funds from the NNSFC forever because he lied about
academic titles and honors using counterfeit certificates.
</P>
<P>
Another teacher is to be denied access to funds over the next
four years for plagiarizing articles, publishing them in foreign
journals and then claiming his research was supported by the NNSFC.
</P>
<P>
In addition, two other applicants who tried to secure funds by
using undeserved titles such as "associate professor" or
concealing pre-doctoral status, would be excluded from applying to
the national natural science fund for next year.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed official said that the healthy development of the
science fund project must be based on truth, and scientific
professionalism should be stressed in China's academic fields.
</P>
</TEXT>
