<HEADLINE> Y2K Efforts Enhanced in Philippine Aviation Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Air
Transportation Office (ATO) has allocated 55.6 million pesos (1.37
million U.S. dollars) to deal with the Y2K computer problem,
Philippine News Agency (PNA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Transportation and Communications Secretary Vicente River was
quoted as saying that the Y2K problem in the aviation sector is
being addressed in earnest by the government.
</P>
<P>
He said that over the past months, the ATO has successfully
completed the end-to-end Y2K testing of its aeronautical fixed
telecommunications network system with its counterpart on the Hong
Kong's Civil Aviation Authority.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, the ATO's mainframe computer has been declared Y2K
compliant after a series of tests and validations.
</P>
<P>
Y2K is a problem referring to computers' inability to reset
their internal clocks for the year 2000. Without adaptation, they
will reset to 1900.
</P>
<P>
The target time for the ATO to make its facilities Y2K ready is
September 30, the significant end of the Y2K Conscious Month
declared earlier by Philippine President Joseph Estrada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
