<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Firmer on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed slightly
firmer on Singapore Stock Market Tuesday as some program buying in
blue chips pushed the benchmark index higher.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) climbed by 5.64 points
to end at 2,105.42 in light trading.
</P>
<P>
The total volume decreased to 169.88 million shares valued at
437.83 million Singapore dollars (about 258.92 million U.S.
dollars). Losers outnumbered gainers by 156 to 133 with 157
counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Gen Int remained at top on the volume list with 29.20 million
shares changing hands. It was followed by AFP which had 22.42
million units traded. GoldenAg was the next with 11.71 million
counters done.
</P>
<P>
DBS and UOB F led the ascent of the day as it ran up 40 cents
to finish at 20.00 and 13.70 Singapore dollars respectively. TIBS
w00 gained 24 cents to close at 1.34 Singapore dollars. DelGro 500
edged up 20 cents to end at 5.70 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH remained the biggest loser of the day as
it dropped 80 cents to close at 27.00 Singapore dollars. SPH 100
sank 70 cents to finish at 27.10 Singapore dollars. GE Life
retreated 30 cents to end at 18.70 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market saw selective buying of Index-linked
stocks such as bank stocks and top actives remained small-cap U.S.
dollar-denominated ones.
</P>
<P>
They said the market's potential upside was seen limited with
the U.S. market closing Monday and investors might look to the
region for cues.
</P>
<P>
Dealers also noted that Cycle &AMP; Carriage (C&AMP;C) continued its
recent fall on fears that its earnings may fall if the company
loses its sole distributorship of Mercedes-Benz cars in Singapore.
 
</P>
