<HEADLINE> Ugandan MPs Demand Investigation in Clashes with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Some Ugandan members of
parliament (MPs) have signed a new motion to investigate the
army's activities in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)
and especially the list of those soldiers killed in recent clashes
with Rwandan troops.
</P>
<P>
More than 28 MPs have signed the motion moved by Aggrey Awori,
an outspoken MP, the Monitor daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Awori was quoted as saying on Monday evening that he was
confident that over 60 legislators would sign the motion by the
end of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
These MPs said that the report of Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni on the DRC issue on August 30 did not touch the essential
issues and they demanded the accountability of the defense budget.
</P>
<P>
Museveni told parliament that a total 38 Ugandan soldiers
including one captain had been killed in clashes with Rwandan
troops in Kisangani, a northern town of the DRC, in mid-August,
the largest ever shoot-out between these two traditional allies
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
President Museveni and Rwandan Vice-President Paul Kagame met
in time to stop the escalation of the war in Kisangani. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
