<HEADLINE> Namibian Diamond Miner Could Become Sector Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Namibian diamond miner
Namco could edge out De Beers as the world's biggest marine
diamond producer within two years, The Star's Business Report said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Namco confirmed last week that it would take effective control
of the Ocean Diamond Mining Holdings (ODM) by buying more shares.
</P>
<P>
The combined production from Namco and ODM could top 360,000
carats in the financial year of 2000 and reach 650,000 carats in
2002, a diamond analyst, Hilton Ashton, estimated Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, they can surpass De Beers Marine (Debmarine) as the
biggest marine diamond producer in the world... depending on just
how much Debmarine's production grows," Ashton w
</P>
<P>
Another industry source, who wished to remain anonymous, was
more bullish in a prediction that the combined Namco/ODM operation
could generate nearly 500,000 carats next year and 780,000 carats
in the financial year of 2001.
</P>
<P>
"By using Namco's technology on ODM's concessions and
upgrading ODM's production methods, the combined group could see a
marked increase in production in the next two years," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
