<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Boost Investment in Rural Joint Ventures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Estrada
will soon launch a program to boost private investors' infusion of
capital and technology into joint ventures in the countryside, a
senior official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Agrarian Reform Secretary Horacio Morales said the joint
venture scheme will not only encourage the private sector to
inject capital and technology in the agricultural sector, but also
boost the government's poverty alleviation and food security
programs.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the guidelines are basically intended to
protect the rights and interest of farmer beneficiaries contrary
to the allegations that these would only favor the landowners,
Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Actually, these guidelines will redound to the benefits of
farmer beneficiaries. Without them, we may have joint venture
agreements that are unfair and disadvantageous to farmers and
farmworkers," Morales explained.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, he said, DAR will not allow the transfer or
sale of land titles or certificates of land ownership award. Only
the "use of the land" will serve as the farmer-beneficiaries'
equity in the joint venture enterprise.
</P>
<P>
Morales said a major condition for the approval of any
arrangement between farmers' groups and the investor is the
retention of land ownership by farmers.
</P>
<P>
"This means the farmers' equity in the venture consists only
of the use of the land and not the land itself, which cannot also
be used to settle obligations of the joint venture," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In this way, farmers' ownership of the land is secure even if
farm operations are jointly managed," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
