</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Supreme Court Monday banned the security services
of the country from applying physical pressure on detainees.
</P>
<P>
In response, Prime Minisiter Ehud Barak said in a statement
that he respects the court's decision, but he noted that the
ruling will "make things very difficult" for the security services
and they need to "find a way" to extract information from a
suspect about an impending attack.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Five Israeli Arabs were arrested Monday on suspicion of
being involved in Sunday's car bombs attacks in two Israeli
cities. Since a gag order was imposed on details relating to the
attacks, little has been disclosed about the police
investigation. 
</P>
