<HEADLINE> Pyongyang Urges Seoul to Recognize Sea Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A commentary of the Korean
Central News Agency on Monday urged South Korea to recognize the
west sea border line declared by Pyongyang last week, saying it
will take firm actions in self-defense against any violations.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and South
Korea ran into naval clashes on June 15 over the disputed waters
along the two countries' west sea border. In the wake of the
incident, the DPRK and the United States held six talks in
Panmunjon on the demarcation of a maritime boundary between the
two Koreas but failed to reach agreement.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK then rejected further talks and on September 2
declared its maritime military control zone which covered all
waters contiguous to five South Korea-controlled islands in the
area with a population of 6,900. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
