<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall, Dollar Rises in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed moderately
lower in Tokyo on Tuesday in sluggish trading as investors were
reluctant to actively buy stocks ahead of Thursday's release of
Japan's gross domestic product (GDP) data for the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped 49.01 points, or 0.28
percent, from Monday's close to end at 17,707.50.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 7.46 points or 0.49 percent to 1,504.62.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to 487.07 million shares
from 450.51 million shares Monday but remained sluggish, staying
below 500 million shares for the third-straight trading day.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank remained as volume leader on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers far
outnumbered gainers by 789 to 398, with 152 issues ending
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar rose against the
yen, briefly surging to 111.00 yen for the first time in a week on
a wave of short covering in the late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
At 5 p.m., the dollar was quoted at 110.79-82 yen, up from 109.
56-59 yen at 9 a.m., and from 109.70-80 yen in London late Monday.
The New York market was closed Monday due to a holiday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
