<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Scientist Wins Award for Marine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A renowned Tanzanian
marine scientist has won a fellowship of 150,000 U.S. dollars for
his contribution to marine conservation.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Magnus Ngoile, Director General of the Tanzanian National
Environment Management Council, won the Pew Marine Conservation
Fellowship from the United States Pew Charitable Trusts, The
Guardian reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
One of the world's largest and most prestigious awards for sea
 preservation, the fellowship is in recognition of Ngoile's
dedication and professional approach in marine conservation.
</P>
<P>
Ngoile's Pew Fellowship resource will be utilized in
establishing a marine reserve in Kilwa, a pristine coastal
district south of Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The district has a coastal strip of about 150 kilometers long
which is full of reefs and historical areas.
</P>
<P>
The Pew-funded project, he said, will not only establish a
marine park but also become the guiding light for future
development and contribute toward a more dynamic economy.
</P>
<P>
Ngoile is the second Tanzanian to win this award. The first
was Professor Adelaide Semesi, who won it in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Up in Kenya's Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreigners invested 1.06
million U.S. dollars in Kenya's stock market in August and only
took away 412,446 dollars, according to the Nairobi Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for the bourse with a net foreign
capital inflow after 11 straight months of a downward spiral, the
East African Standard newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But brokers noted that it did not mean that foreigners'
appetite for Nairobi stocks was on a rise, nor did it signal an
end to the market's recent misfortunes.
</P>
<P>
They said foreign investors bought heavily in only one company,
the East African Breweries Limited, which accounted for 97.4
percent of the total foreign inflows.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi stock market has struggled to recover since 1997
when the International Monetary Fund (IMF) suspended a loan
package to Kenya on grounds of runaway corruption and poor
governance in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
The country's retreating economy and poor corporate profits
have weakened Nairobi's main 20-share index to its lowest level in
six year, with a drop of 15.9 percent since the start of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Local brokers expected that in the coming few months it was
mainly the Breweries company to lure foreign investors to the
market.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts pointed out that a rise in treasury bill
yields showed the government was not cutting down on its
expenditure, encouraging investors' focus on the money market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
