<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Check Enforcement of Compulsory Education Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A nationwide campaign is to be
launched by China's highest legislature to check how the law on
compulsory education for all has been enforced in a bid to ensure
that the nine-year compulsory education is basically realized by
early next year.
</P>
<P>
Five inspection teams, each headed by a vice-chairman from the
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, will set out
in September and October to visit five provinces, autonomous
regions and the municipalities of Henan, Chongqing, Hubei,
Xinjiang and Guangxi.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest problems in the education field at present are the
shortage of funds and teachers as well as the low proficiency
level of teachers in poverty-stricken areas," said Peng Peiyun,
vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee who stressed that
these issues will top the inspection teams' agenda.
</P>
<P>
Since the law was enacted in 1986, it is estimated that its
target of providing education for all eligible youngsters by the
end of 1998 has, in most areas, reached a 73-percent success level.
And nine provinces and the municipalities of Beijing, Tianjin and
Shanghai report a 100-percent implementation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
