<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Check Enforcement of Compulsory Education Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, according to Peng, in poverty-stricken areas only two
percent of the counties had fully met the standards up to last
year, which she insists is not satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of investment in education, 23 provinces, autonomous
regions and municipalities have failed to spend enough money
according to the law," she said, explaining that it strictly
stipulates that the annual increase of educational funds shall be
more than the increase of revenue.
</P>
<P>
The situation in poor regions of China is graver than others,
because local governments have a certain reputation for delaying
the payment of teachers' salaries or merely writing them IOUs.
</P>
<P>
Peng also called for special attention to be paid to the still
large number of girl dropouts in poor areas. "The educational
background of girls will determine to some extent the professional
standards of Chinese citizens in the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
The other four vice-chairmen heading the inspection groups are
He Luli, Cheng Siwei, Xu Jialu and Jiang Zhenghua.
</P>
<P>
Besides listening to reports from local government bodies, the
legislators will also conduct surveys among teachers, parents and
students, as well as looking into the condition of school
buildings.  
</P>
