<HEADLINE> Some 300 HIV/AIDS People to Attend Int'l AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- About 300 people living with
HIV/AIDS worldwide have confirmed their coming to the forthcoming
11th International Conference on AIDS and STDS (sexual transmitted
diseases) in Africa (ICASA) scheduled for September 12-16 in
Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Network for Zambian People Living With HIV/AIDS coordinator
Winston Zulu said the representation at the conference was
encouraging because many people were HIV positive and they wanted
what was good for HIV/AIDS people.
</P>
<P>
The Times of Zambia newspaper Tuesday quoted Zulu as saying the
village set up by ICASA during the conference will focus on the
needs of people living with HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"We have been given a chance to organize ourselves and this
chance has come at this conference. Issues like treatment,
medication and human rights are typical problems affecting people
living with HIV/AIDS and that is what we hope to look at," Zulu
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the conference also gave Zambians a chance to receive
the best awareness there ever was.
</P>
<P>
According to ICASA organizing committee, more than 100
delegates to the conference have arrived in the Zambia capital and
the United Nations delegation has stated its advisory workshop on
human resource development and strategic planning process here.
</P>
