<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Calls for Enhanced Sino-Australian Trade Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MELBOURNE, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin called for efforts to strengthen economic and trade
cooperation between China and Australia in several areas at the
Sino-Australian trade and investment Summit held here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, Jiang said, it is important to constantly explore new
areas for trade while continuing to develop trade in the
traditional areas. For example, Australia may take a more active
part in the market competition in China in such areas as energy
and environmental protection while some Chinese industries such as
household electric appliances and telecom also have opportunities
for big development in the Australian market.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, China has identified the infrastructure and pillar
industries as its priorities for development and Australian
business community is welcome to invest in these areas.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, China and Australia have their respective advantages
in science and technology and have accumulated rich experience.
This has afforded the two countries an opportunity to draw upon
each other's useful experience and make up for each other's
deficiencies to the benefit of their common progress.
</P>
<P>
Fourthly, China and Australia should increase consultation and
cooperation in APEC and international financial institutions and
make joint efforts for Ecotech and the reform of the international
financial system.
</P>
<P>
Jiang briefed the participants at the seminar on China's
opening up and modernization drive and reviewed the development of
Sino-Australian economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the past two decades or so have witnessed a rapid
development of the economic and trade relations between China and
Australia. Especially since the beginning of the 1990s, the
development of this relationship has picked up momentum. The
economic cooperation and two-way trade have expanded further in
terms of the areas they cover and the bilateral trade volume has
kept growing for seven years in a run.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Jiang's speech, Premier of the State of Victoria
Jefferey Kennett and Deputy Prime Minister of Australia John
Anderson also addressed the summit.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 Australian officials and representatives from the
Australian industrial and commercial circles attended the summit.
Also present were Chinese Vice Premier Qian Qichen and other
members of Jiang's entourage.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president held separate talks earlier in the day
with Governor of the Victoria State James Gobbo and Premier
Kennett, who extended cordial welcome to him.
</P>
<P>
Jiang thanked the government and people of the State of
Victoria for their warm hospitality accorded him since his arrival
in Melbourne. The Sino-Australian relations have witnessed
considerable development thanks to the joint efforts of both
sides, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said this year marks the 20th anniversary of the
establishment of the sisterly relationship between the State of
Victoria and China's Jiangsu Province. He hoped that the two sides
will continuously expand the mutually beneficial cooperation into
new areas.
</P>
<P>
Also in the morning, Jiang visited a research institute on
bionic ears, and met with members of the Chinese general consulate
in Melbourne, representatives from China-funded institutions as
well as representatives of Chinese students studying in Australia,
ethnic Chinese and Chinese nationals living in Australia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
