<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 08:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Press Highlights Visit of Jordanian King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah
Bin Hussein's ongoing visit to Kuwait is being felt strongly here
Tuesday morning, especially in the local press.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's major newspapers, both Arabic and English, carried
front-page headline stories and big photos concerning the trip by
the Jordanian monarch and his wife Queen Rania Al-Abdullah, who
was brought up in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
It seems that old memories have given way to the new desire of
both sides to turn "a new page in the history of the long and deep
relations" between Jordan and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah was quoted by the newspapers as saying upon his
arrival for the visit on Monday that "passing difference will not
affect the development of relations between the two Arab states."
</P>
<P>
Jordanian-Kuwaiti links were all but broken as King Abdullah's
late father, King Hussein, failed to stand by Kuwait during the
1990 Gulf crisis resulted from Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Kuwait began the rapprochement process more than
two years ago, after Kuwait expressed its desire to improve its
ties with all Arab states except Iraq, which was meanwhile
distanced by Amman itself.
</P>
<P>
As Queen Rania was born in Kuwait 29 years ago to a Jordanian
family of Palestinian origin, her whirlwind trip Monday to
Kuwait's New English School, Rania's alma mater, and the house she
used to live in arrested no less attention than her husband's
encounter with Kuwaiti officials.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian Queen, once a successful and popular student,
was overwhelmingly greeted by school teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
Since Kuwaiti officials had ruled out any specific agenda
during Abdullah's two-day stay, analysts here believe that
sensitive issues that could revive the old unpleasant memories
may not be touched upon in bilateral talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
