<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Copper Receipts Hit Lowest Rate in 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's gross metal receipts
have steadily been reducing, with the latest figure hitting the
lowest in the past six years, according to the July macroeconomic
indicators available here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures for copper receipts for the first six months
of this year closed at 156.9 million U.S. dollars compared to
272.4 million dollars during the same period in 1998. Cobalt
results were at 194.4 million dollars for January to June this
year, while the amount accrued during 1998 was at 331.6 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The results from the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM),
the major player in the country, have been slumping, both for
copper and cobalt.
</P>
<P>
The ZCCM, for the first half last year had receipts amounting
to 194.8 million dollars, dropping to 131.6 million dollars as at
June since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The receipts for the past six years show copper starting with
790.3 million dollars in 1992, reaching 578.6 million dollars in
1995 and 533.89 million dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Analysts at Barclays bank said in their latest quarterly report
that the continued degradation in earnings from the mining sector
is severely impacting on the national economy, and replacement
economic activity will not be created in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Observers also said Zambia's mining industry should have taken
advantage of the rise in copper prices experienced at the London
Metal Exchange, closing at 74.29 U.S. cents per pound as at July
this year.
</P>
<P>
The lowest recorded was at 62 cents per pound in March this
year, and has since being going up, with analysts saying this
could be as a result of the up-looking international market,
especially in East Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
