<HEADLINE> East Timor's Pro-Independence Leader Xanana Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- East Timor's pro-independence
leader Xanana Gusmao has been released based on an amnesty granted
by the Indonesian president on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The amnesty was signed by President B.J. Habibie and Minister
for Justice/State Secretary Muladi as the government's
representative at the office of the Justice Ministry Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
"Xanana was released today and now I hand him over to UNAMET
(United Nations Mission in East Timor) ... I hope Xanana can
participate actively in settling problems in East Timor," Muladi
said after signing the amnesty.
</P>
<P>
Although Xanana has been handed over to UNAMET, the Indonesian
government is still responsible for his safety and security as he
is still in the Indonesian territory, Muladi said.
</P>
<P>
On where Xanana would be freed, Muladi said Xanana would not be
brought to Dili, capital of East Timor, or another area in East
Timor before the situation in the former Portuguese colony is
safe.
</P>
<P>
"But one day he must be there," he added.
</P>
<P>
Xanana, president of the East Timor Resistance Council (CNRT),
was arrested by Indonesian troops in East Timor on November 20,
1992. He was imposed a life sentence by Dili court on May 21, 1993
for illegal arms possession.
</P>
<P>
Then, his sentence was commuted by former president Soeharto to
20 years and three months after a Dili court's decision.
</P>
<P>
He was in Cipinang prison for five years before being
transferred to a detention house near the Salemba prison in
Central Jakarta in February 1999 as part of the government's
effort to help the peaceful process of solution to the East Timor
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
