<HEADLINE> World Ancient City Conference Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Ancient City
Conference, which was scheduled for mid-September in the capital
of Shaanxi Province, northwest China, has been postponed because
of the recent earthquake in Turkey that prevented the mayor of
Istanbul from coming on time.
</P>
<P>
And the new date of the meeting has not yet been set, an
official with the organizing committee said today.
</P>
<P>
The conference is expected to gather mayors of the world's five
ancient capitals: Athens, Istanbul, Cairo, Rome, and Xi'an. A
proposal of Xi'an last year called for mayors and representatives
to meet regularly in the five cities to discuss urban protection,
construction, planning, and cultural heritage protection.
</P>
<P>
They also plan to organize cultural, academic and information
exchange programs when they meet.
</P>
<P>
The five are the birthplace of Eastern and Western culture and
have a great deal of historical significance and large numbers of
cultural relics and, therefore, face similar tasks in protecting
their cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
</TEXT>
