<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Former Rebel Leader Plays Down Internal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Foday Sankoh, Sierra Leone's
former rebel leader Monday played down a growing rift in his camp
and promised a quick solution to the present hostage drama when
visiting Abidjan, capital of Cote d'Iovire.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh said he planned to go to rebel-controlled territory to
smooth differences between his Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
and renegade soldiers allied with it, according to reports
available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"They are looking for trouble. But this is proof to the world
that RUF has not been the problem in Sierra Leone," Sankoh added.
</P>
<P>
The renegade soldiers demanding a better deal under a July
peace accord to end the nine-year civil war in Sierra Leone have
kidnapped two RUF commanders preparing Sankoh's return home.
</P>
<P>
The ex-soldiers, who control towns and territory north of the
capital Freetown, had abducted scores of foreign hostages for
about a week early last month to press for similar demands.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh said he was directing negotiations with the abductors
and expected his commanders to be freed soon.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader said he expected to be in Cote d'Ivoire for a
few more days for a possible meeting with President Henri Konan
Bedie and Foreign Minister Essy Amara.
</P>
<P>
Both men were in Libya Monday for a special summit of the
Organization of African Unity (OUA) after attending a meeting of
heads of state of the Francophonie movement in Canada. From
Cote d'Ivoire, Sankoh plans to go first to Liberia to meet
President Charles Taylor, who is close to both the RUF and the
former soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Because of renewed tension in Sierra Leone, Nigeria at the
weekend suspended a pullout of its 12,000 troops spearheading a
regional force defending the Freetown government since 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
