<HEADLINE> Chinese Defense Minister Meets Czech Guests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Defense Minister Chi
Haotian has told Jiri Sedivy, visiting chief of the General Staff
of the armed forces of the Czech Republic, that his trip will
undoubtedly enhance the existing bond of trust and friendship
between the two countries and military services.
</P>
<P>
Chi, who is also a vice-chairman of the Central Military
Commission and a State Councilor, said the Chinese government and
its armed forces attach considerable importance to the growth of
ties with its Czech counterparts in every aspect.
</P>
<P>
"It doesn't matter what has occurred in the international arena,
both the bilateral state and military relationships have kept
steady growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the Taiwan issue, Chi pointed out that national unification
is the common aspiration of the 1.2 billion Chinese people, as
well as those living in Taiwan, stressing that the Chinese people
oppose any attempt to create "two Chinas", "one China, one Taiwan"
or "independence for Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
The malicious "two states" remarks by Lee Teng-hui is a ploy to
divide China, he said. The expected reunification will be realized
by peaceful means under the policy of "one country and two systems
" as expounded by the Chinese government, Chi declared.
</P>
<P>
"However, China will not commit itself to abandon the use of
force in this issue, for it will not target the Taiwan people but
those hostile forces working both on and outside the island of
Taiwan to split China," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Chi also briefed Sedivy and his party on China's current
domestic situation and the army's construction.
</P>
<P>
Sedivy extended his congratulations for the forthcoming 50th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China. He
expressed his belief that as developing countries, Czech and China
could explore new areas of cooperation in terms of the military
and in general.  
</P>
