<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Continue Lowering Import Tariffs: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MELBOURNE, September 7 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to lower
its import tariffs for industrial products to 15 percent next year
and to 10 percent before the year 2005, Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said here Tuesday in a speech delivered at the Australia-
China Trade and Investment Summit.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said China will, as always, actively participate in
international economic cooperation and improve its all-direction,
multi-dimension and wide-range opening-up pattern.
</P>
<P>
China has opened more areas for foreign-funded banks to deal in
RMB business and for pilot projects of Sino-foreign joint ventures
in foreign trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the future, we will provide opportunities for trade in
services such as foreign investments in the banking, insurance,
tourism, retail, foreign trade and legal services, while stepping
up opening-up efforts in the energy, transportation,
communications and other infrastructure industries," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leader also promised to improve the country's legal
system to create a better environment for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
"We will further improve the system of laws and regulations on
foreign investment, protect the rights and interests of foreign-
funded enterprises in strict compliance with law, protect
intellectual property rights and improve service for foreign-
invested enterprises," he said.
</P>
<P>
With the steady progress in economic and social development,
Jiang said, the enormous potentialities of the Chinese market will
be further tapped.
</P>
<P>
According to Jiang, China is expected to import 1.5 trillion U.
S. dollars' worth of goods during the coming seven years.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that in the first decade of the next century, the
Chinese economy is expected to maintain a relatively high growth
rate.
</P>
<P>
The prospects for economic cooperation and trade between China
and the rest of the world will be "even broader," Jiang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
