<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Researcher Says Educational TV Needs To Be More Appealing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Very few primary and middle
school students in China watch educational TV that is directed at
them, according to a recent survey by the China Juvenile Research
Center (CJRC).
</P>
<P>
The study of 6,742 students and their parents from the cities
of Beijing, Tianjin, and Shanghai municipalities, and Liaoning,
Shaanxi, Shandong, Jiangxi, Henan, Sichuan and Guangdong provinces
finds that only 1.1 percent of the senior middle school students
watch educational TV and 2.9 percent of junior middle school
students and 9.6 percent of primary school students do.
</P>
<P>
Senior and junior middle school students favor series (34.6
percent and 27.1 percent respectively), while primary school
students love cartoons (36.9 percent).
</P>
<P>
China's educational TV mainly focuses on English, math, and
physics, according to CJRC's deputy director Sun Yunxiao, and
these programs are often pedestrian and not visually appealing,
with rigid presentation. They are simply a copy of classroom
teaching and lack creativity.
</P>
<P>
Chinese students are burdened with hard work and are certain to
want to change the channel when the programs are no different from
the classroom, Sun says. The quality of educational TV needs to be
improved and its presentation as well. TV programs, as a form of
entertainment, should help students in a more relaxed way observe
society and broaden their outlook while providing information.
</P>
<P>
Educational TV needs to make use of the advantages of modern
communications techniques, he says. Over 90 percent of the parents
polled said that they limit the amount of TV their children watch
because they worry about unsuitable programs affecting their study
habits or excessive watching ruining their eyesight. Many of them
however, while encouraging their children to watch educational TV,
are not satisfied with the programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Affairs Conference Held in Phnom Penh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A three-day conference on
gender and development in Cambodia opened here Tuesday to help
improve the status of Cambodian women and to push for social,
economic and political changes.
</P>
<P>
The first such national conference was opened by Queen Norodom
Monineath Sihanouk at Le Royal Hotel. More than 200 women leaders,
government officials and NGO representatives attended the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference is scheduled to review the achievements made by
Cambodian women since the Fourth World Conference on Women held in
Beijing in 1995 and to put forward the action plan of the Royal
Government of Cambodia for the advancement of women in the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
The conference will also feature 10 panel discussions on such
topics as health, education, prostitution and human trafficking.
</P>
<P>
While significant progress has been made in drafting and
passing legislation to protect the rights of women, law
enforcement is weak. Discrimination and violence against women
remain a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
Mu Sochua, minister of women and veterans' affairs, told
reporters that the ministry will focus the priority in the next
few years on the publicity and education among women, the
protection of women's rights and the enhancement of women's
training.
</P>
<P>
Cambodian women play an active role in the country's economy
and civil society, and constitute 53 percent of the active labor
force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
