<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0120 GMT, September 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Commission said Monday that it has
approved humanitarian aid worth a total of 13.85 million euros (14.
68 million U.S. dollars) for the Middle East,Romania, the Ethiopia-
Eritrea region and Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) executive branch said the aid will
support the humanitarian projects to be carried out in these areas
for up to nine months.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippine government will work harder to keep
the prices of rice and other basic commodities steady, Philippine
News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Edno Joson, head of the National Food Authority (NFA), said his
agency continues to sell rice at 14 pesos (one dollar is equal to
40 pesos) per kilo, and that he does not foresee any increase in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysia Monday urged the country's fishery
sector to increase fish output to meet the demand of the
increasing population in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Sulaiman Daud made the appeal when
launching the aquaculture code of practice in the northern state
of Pulau Pinang, Bernama news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DHAKA -- Minister for Commerce and Industries Tofail Ahmed has
expressed the hope that Bangladesh's annual export earnings would
reach 10 billion U.S. dollars very soon from the current level of
5.3 billion provided the government and private sector work
closely to diversify export items.
</P>
<P>
To increase export earnings Bangladesh will have to diversify
its export items as well as explore export markets with a view to
finding out new areas where its products can be sold, he said
while addressing the launch ceremony of Bangladesh Export
Diversification Project (BDXDP) Saturday, according to the Daily
Star Monday.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile and Central American nations will sign a free
trade treaty on October 25 in Santiago as expected at the second
summit of the states of the Americas (SOA) held last year.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of Costa Rica, El Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala and
Nicaragua will visit Chile from October 24 to 26 for the event.
</P>
