<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Jiang Zemin's Speech in Melbourne </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MELBOURNE, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The following is the full
text of Chinese President Jiang Zemin's speech at the Australia-
China Trade and Investment Summit in Melbourne Tuesday.
The Honourable John Anderson, Deputy Prime Minister of Australia,
The Honourable Jefferey Kennett,Premier of the State of Victoria,
Ladies and Gentlemen,
</P>
<P>
First of all, I would like to thank the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs and Trade of Australia, the Government of the State of
Victoria and the Australia-China Business Council for their kind
invitation which has given me the opportunity to attend the
luncheon hosted by the Australia-China Trade and Investment Summit.
Over a long period of time, friends from the business communities
of our two countries have done a lot of effective work in
promoting Sino-Australian trade and economic cooperation and
enhancing the friendship between our two peoples. I would like to
take this opportunity to extend my heartfelt thanks and best
wishes to you and, through you, to the business communities of our
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of Sino-Australian diplomatic relations,
our bilateral economic relations and trade have maintained a good
momentum of development, which has injected great vitality to the
development of Sino-Australian relations. Today, at the approach
of a new century, it is of great significance for people from the
business communities of out two countries to meet here in
Melbourne and discuss the cross-century development of our
bilateral economic cooperation and trade.
</P>
<P>
Now, with your permission, I would like to brief you on the
reform, opening-up and modernisation drive in China.
</P>
<P>
The reform and opening-up have been going on in China for more
than 20 years. During this period, China has enjoyed a sustained,
rapid and healthy economic development and an all-round social
progress. Its GDP grew at an average annual rate of 9.7% in the
period from 1979 to 1998. It is the seventh largest economy in the
world in terms of the economic aggregates. Its foreign trade and
economic cooperation have been expanding continuously. It has
established economic and trading ties with 220 countries and
regions and it is now the eleventh largest trading nation in the
world. The social productive forces in China, its aggregate
national strength and its people's living standards have all
improved by leaps and bounds. All undertakings have registered an
all-round development. We have withstood the test of the impact of
the Asian financial crisis, devoted much of our attention to the
tackling of the new problems that have cropped up in the course of
development and maintained the overall stability for economic
growth and social progress. China will enter the 21st century with
a thriving economy and vigorous modernisation endeavour.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, we are implementing a pro-active fiscal policy
and expanding domestic demand. We have worked to stabilize and
strengthen agriculture, step up the development of infrastructure,
deepen the reform of state-owned enterprises, adjust economic
structure, expand urban and rural markets, increase export and
absorb foreign capital. Work in all areas is progressing orderly.
As a result, in the first half of this year, the economic growth
rate was kept at 7.6%. State-owned enterprises started to have
better economic returns, state revenue increased, the financial
sector was operating smoothly and the RMB exchange rate remained
stable. In the second half of this year, we will make better use
of such means of macro regulation and control as fiscal, monetary
and investment policies, so as to stimulate consumption,
investment and export. All the development objectives set for this
year will be attained.
</P>
<P>
The period from now to 2010 will be crucial for China's reform
and development. In this period, we expect to establish a
relatively full-fledged socialist market economic system and
maintain a sustained, rapid and sound development of the national
economy. To this end, we will stick to and improve the basic
economic system with the public ownership as the mainstay and
other economic sectors developing side by side. We will actively
introduce all those forms of business operation and organization
that reflect the law of the social production, including joint
stock system. We will continue to stabilize and accelerate the
agricultural development, unswervingly carry out the reform and
development of state-owned enterprises and gradually establish a
modern enterprise system. We will continue to make strategic
adjustments to the economic structure, accelerate the process of
optimising industrial structure, vigorously promote coordinated
development of regional economy, spare no efforts in developing
new- and high-tech industries, and develop an IT-based economy at
an accelerated pace. We will continue to implement the strategy of
sustainable development and that of rejuvenating the country
through science and education so as to continuously beef up the
sustainable economic and social development in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Jiang Zemin's Speech in Melbourne </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has a population of over 1.2 billion and a huge market.
With the steady progress in the economic and social development,
the enormous potentialities of the Chinese market will be further
tapped. The total import volume for the coming 7 years is expected
to reach US$1.5 trillion. In the first decade of the next century,
the Chinese economy is expected to maintain a relatively high
growth rate. The prospects for economic cooperation and trade
between China and the rest of the world will be even broader.
</P>
<P>
The past two decades or so have witnessed a rapid development
of the economic relations and trade between China and Australia.
Especially since the beginning of the 1990s, the development of
this relationship has picked up momentum. The economic cooperation
and two-way trade have expanded further in terms of the areas they
cover and the bilateral trade volume have kept growing for seven
years in a run. By the end of 1998, it rose to over US$5 billion.
Now China is Australia's fifth largest trading partner, seventh
largest export market and biggest purchaser of its wool. And
Australia is China's ninth largest trading partner, fourth largest
export market and the largest recipient of China's investment. By
the end of the first half of this year, there were 3687 Australia-
invested projects in China, with a contractual investment of over
U.S. $ 5.6 billion. China's investment in Australia has increased
year by year, and the number of Chinese enterprises and agencies
in Australia have amounted to 170 now. Our two countries have
conducted extensive cooperation in such fields as agriculture,
forestry, animal husbandry, energy, mineral resources,
transportation, textile, building materials and urban renovation,
and this cooperation has produced good results. Four Australian
banks have opened offices and branches in China and one has
established a joint-venture insurance company in Shanghai. The
Chinese Government has recently approved the application by two
Australian law firms to open offices in China, which is another
progress in the economic cooperation and trade between China and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
Sino-Australian economic cooperation and trade have expanded
from bilateral to regional and multi-lateral fields. In the wake
of the Asian financial crisis, China and Australia held effective
consultations and cooperation with each other on how to dissolve
the crisis, stabilize regional economy and promote the reform of
the international financial system. Our two countries have since
maintained good coordination in APEC and international financial
institutions, and made efforts for economic development in the
Asia-Pacific and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
An important reason for the steady development of Sino-
Australian economic relations and trade lies in the strong
complementarity of our two economies. China has abundant human
resources and a vast market. It has also made major headway in
science and technology. We can provide Australia not only with
labor-intensive products but also with such technology-intensive
services as satellite launching. Australia has abundant natural
resources. The iron ore, aluminum, grain and wool that Australia
produces are in great demand in the Chinese market. Australia also
has fairly developed high technologies, so there are huge
potentials for cooperation between us in the scientific and
technological field.
</P>
<P>
For the next period, China will focus on the development of
such infrastructure and basic industries as water conservancy,
energy, transportation, telecom, raw materials, environmental
protection, high-tech industries and major equipment. Take
environmental protection as an example. The annual output value of
China's environmental protection industry is expected to grow by
15-20% on an average in the next decade and to reach over U.S.$35
billion by 2010. Melbourne and the state of Victoria, Australia,
have a competitive edge in terms of capital and technology in the
above-mentioned fields and there is a broad prospect for
cooperation between our two sides in these areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Jiang Zemin's Speech in Melbourne </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MELBOURNE, September 7 (Xinhua) -- In addition, China will step
up the development and opening-up of its western and central areas.
These regions are vast in area and rich in natural resources. They
have thus got great potentials for development. To accelerate the
development of the western and central areas is a major strategic
objective that is vital to the implementation of China's trans-
century development program. We hope that the business community
in Australia will make good use of your rich experience and
advanced technologies in the development of resources to
participate in China's development of its western and central
areas.
</P>
<P>
Looking into the future, I believe it is important for us to
strengthen cooperation in the following four areas.
</P>
<P>
1. To constantly explore new areas for trade while continuing
to develop trade in the traditional areas. For example, Australia
may take a more active part in the market competition in China in
such areas as energy and environmental protection while some
Chinese industries such as household electric appliances and
telecom also have opportunities for big development in the
Australian market.
</P>
<P>
2. China has identified the infrastructure and pillar
industries as its priorities for development and Australian
business community is welcome to invest in these areas.
</P>
<P>
3. China and Australia have their respective advantages in
science and technology and have accumulated rich experience. This
has afforded the two countries an opportunity to draw upon each
other's useful experience and make up for each other's
deficiencies to the benefit of their common progress.
</P>
<P>
4. China and Australia should increase consultation and
cooperation in APEC and international financial institutions and
make joint efforts for Ecotech and the reform of the international
financial system.
</P>
<P>
To develop Sino-Australian economic relations and trade, a
sound and stable political relationship between our two countries
is required, and the growth of the former will in turn help
promote the development of the latter. A virtuous pattern of
interrelated and interactive political, economic and trade
relationship is in the common interests of our two peoples. It is
our hope that the far-sighted businessmen and entrepreneurs from
both sides will view and conduct our bilateral economic relations
and two-way trade on a long-term basis and make joint efforts for
continued progress of Sino-Australian friendly relations and
mutually-beneficial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In conclusion, I would like to wish the Australia-China Trade
and Investment Summit a complete success.
</P>
<P>
Thank you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
