<HEADLINE> Thai Economy to Grow 3 Percent in 2000: State Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's economy is expected
to grow around three percent next year with the help of a series
of economic stimulus measures, The Nation reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The National Economic and Social Development Board (NESDB) said
at a weekly meeting of economic ministers Monday that the
projected growth in 2000 would be a product of various stimulus
measures implemented by the government in the past year.
</P>
<P>
The state agency said that the baht would trade in the range of
36 to 37 against the greenback next year while inflation is likely
to increase slightly to three percent.
</P>
<P>
On the external accounts, Thailand would have a trade surplus
next year equal to 5.5 percent of GDP and a current account
surplus of 8.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government launched three stimulus packages in a
one-year period. In August last year, the government unveiled a
package to help banks recapitalize, in April this year a 3.5
billion dollars plan on extra fiscal spending and in August this
year a 3 billion dollars package aiming to boost investment in the
productive sector of industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
