<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volunteers Complete Internet-Based Life Experiment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese volunteers
spent 72 hours connected only to the Internet in an experiment
that ended on Monday and found it is still a difficult thing to
use electronic currency for on-line payment in China.
</P>
<P>
The experiment brought together 12 people from the three cities
of Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou. One of the 12 was taken out of
the program half-way through because of a lack of on-line
experience. The other 11 lived in closely-monitored conditions
with only the Internet to communicate with the outside world and
used it to get their daily food, clothing, bedding, cosmetics, and
toiletries, as well as more frivolous items.
</P>
<P>
None of the volunteers was able to persuade people to accept
their electronic currency as payment and had to pay cash for
everything. One person tried five or six websites to pay with
electronic currency, but failed.
</P>
<P>
One analyst says that the test is a good way to check on China'
s networks and the IT industry.
</P>
<P>
The experiment was sponsored by a dozen media organizations.
More than 5,000 people applied via the net to take part and the
final people were chosen by psychologists. They were then given 1,
500 yuan in cash and 1,500 yuan in electronic currency for the
test.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Information Industry, Chinese
networks have been developing at a surprisingly rapid pace. In
1998, there were 2.1 million net users. That figure went to more
than four million by the first half of this year, so the Ministry
is eager to learn how the network will affect people's lives in
the future.
</P>
<P>
The three-day experiment got people's attention nationwide. One
elderly man in Shanghai said that he used to think of the computer
as something only for engineers and scientists and something that
had nothing to do with ordinary people, but he now finds it
closely linked to people's daily lives.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible that people may entirely depend on it, some day,
" he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Novotna to Retire from Tennis at the End of 1999 (Updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Former Wimbledon champion
Jana Novotna of the Czech Republic, a standout in women's tennis
throughout the decade, Monday announced she is retiring at the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
Novotna, who will turn 31 on October 2, made her announcement
Monday at the U.S. Open. Bothered by an ankle injury, Novotna was
seeded eighth at the U.S. Open but lost 6-3, 6-3 in the third
round to Anke Huber of Germany.
</P>
<P>
"I've decided to finish this year, fulfill my obligations for
this fall and then not to play any more next year," Novotna said.
"I think I have been thinking about the decision for a very long
time. I just felt that the timing for it is right."
</P>
<P>
Novotna's retirement announcement comes less than a month after
her long-time rival Steffi Graf of Germany announced her
retirement.
</P>
<P>
The sight of Novotna sobbing on the shoulder of the Dutchess of
Kent at the awards ceremony after blowing a third-set lead and
losing the 1993 Wimbledon final to Graf is one the most pognant in
tennis history.
</P>
<P>
She lost to Martina Hinigs in the 1997 final but defeated
Nathalie Tauziat at the All-England Club the following year for
her only Grand Slam title.
</P>
<P>
Novotna, who joined the WTA Tour in 1987 and has been ranked as
high as second in the world, won 23 singles titles and stamped
herself as one of the greatest doubles players in history with 73
titles, including 12 in Grand Slam events.
</P>
<P>
The fact that her retirement comes so close behind Graf's was
not lost on Novotna.
</P>
<P>
"It was an under 14 and I happened to play Steffi Graf in the
opening round. She's been there for a very long time. It is pretty
ironic and incredible that we are retiring at the same year
basically."
</P>
<P>
Novotna noted she and Graf were leaving a women's tennis tour
that is peaking in popularity with the emergence of a number of
talented young players.
</P>
<P>
"I just feel that the women's tour nowadays is strong than ever.
I think that the younger players and the new generation is ready
to take over. As we will see maybe next year, some of the older
players will retire. The new generation is ready to take the step
ahead and be at the top and just lead the way." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
