<HEADLINE> Germany Provides Rice to Sri Lanka for Food Security Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Germany has agreed to provide
Sri Lanka 1,000 tons of rice towards a food security project in a
civil war-ravaged district, the German Embassy here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The rice worth 26.4 million rupees (365,000 U.S. dollars) will
be donated to the Integrated Food Security Project (IFSP),
launched in the eastern Trincomalee district in August 1998, the
embassy said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time that Germany sends rice to Sri Lanka for
the IFSP. The German government arranged to supply 500 tons of
rice towards the project in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
The IFSP is implemented by the Ministry of Plan Implementation
through the District Planning Secretariat with the German Agency
for Technical Cooperation (GTZ) as co-partner.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the project is to redevelop and reconstruct
the lives of persons displaced until 1995 by the ethnic conflict
and were resettled by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been plagued by a 16-year-old war between the
Sinhalese majority dominated government and the Tamil minority
rebels who demand a separate homeland in the north and east of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The IFSP also seeks to diversify and intensify the nutrition
base and income opportunities of the conflict affected target
groups at food risk to improve their nutrition habits and health
care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
