<HEADLINE> State of Emergency Declared in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A state of emergency was
declared in East Timor on Tuesday morning, chief of the
Information Center of the Indonesian National Defense Forces (TNI)
Brig. Gen. Sudrajat said here.
</P>
<P>
He said the period of emergency started from 00:00 local time
Tuesday (17:00 GMT Monday) until the situation returns to normal.
</P>
<P>
The situation in East Timor has become tense since the
announcement of the direct ballot result on September 4.
</P>
<P>
Reports said dozens of people have been killed in the clashes
between pro-integration and pro-independence forces in the last
three days.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian National Police Chief Gen. Roesmanhadi said here
Monday night the situation in Dili, capital of East Timor, was
grim.
</P>
<P>
"The region is not yet calm. It is still out of control. The
government there is not functioning," he said.
</P>
<P>
The August 30 direct ballot showed that 344,580 voters or 78.5
percent chose independence against 94,388 voters or 21.5 percent
preferring wide-ranging autonomy.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony annexed by Indonesia in
1976, has been seen by the United Nations General Assembly as a
non-self-governing territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
