<HEADLINE> Libyan Leader Calls for Comprehensive African Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TRIPOLI, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Libyan leader Muammar Ghaddafi
Monday called for a fully comprehensive African unity to bring
about freedom to the African continent.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the opening of a preparatory meeting of the
Council of Ministers held here, Ghaddafi expressed his belief that
"there should be unity" in the African continent in order to face
the challenges of the new century.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting will pave the way for the fourth
Extraordinary Session of the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
to be held in the Libyan city of Sirte Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of African countries are eager to see Africa free and
united to realize development and liberation of their countries,
"an objective" as termed by the Libyan leader.
</P>
<P>
"Europe is uniting before us," and there have been contacts and
discussions among African heads of state and government to lay out
the guidelines for "the United States of Africa," said Ghaddafi.
</P>
<P>
It will be possible for the OAU Charter to be amended with
unanimous approach and common determination, Ghaddafi added.
</P>
<P>
The Charter of the 53-member OAU has not been revised since it
was signed in Addis Ababa by 31 heads of state and government on
May 25, 1963.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the Arab League Ahamed Meguid and
Secretary General of the OAU Salim Ahamed Salim and foreign
ministers and their representatives from 32 African countries
attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day summit, the heads of state and government of
the OAU will discuss ways and means to strengthen the 36-year-old
continental organization to make it more effective to keep pace
with the social, political and economic developments taking place
within the context of globalization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
