<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kyrgyzstan Says Militants Still Holding Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Kyrgyzstan Foreign
Ministry said Monday that the government will eliminate the
militants entrenched in the south of the country and rescue the
hostages.
</P>
<P>
A month ago, 400 militants invaded the area of Osh in the south
of Kyrgyzstan near Tajikistan. The militants are currently "holed
up" in a mountainous village and are still holding 12 hostages,
including Shamkeyev, the commander of the interior ministry troops,
and four Japanese geologists.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency of Kyrgyzstan has said there is no
reason to exaggerate the seriousness of the situation there, and
the incident will not affect the stability and safety of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
All the offices, enterprises, airports and railway stations in
the area of Osh are operating,it added.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyzstan is preparing for the Third Central Asian Games which
begins in October. Everything is going smoothly here, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Officials noted that the present situation in Kyrgyzstan will
not threaten the security of foreigners traveling in the county.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the Russian Foreign Ministry, Kazakhstan,
Uzbekistan and Tajikistan are consulting over joint efforts to
rescue hostages and stop the terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
