<HEADLINE> Russia, Yugoslavia Insist on Strict Observance of UN Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Yugoslavia
insisted Monday that the U.N. Security Council resolution 1244
must be strictly observed and the state sovereignty and
territorial integrity of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia must
be respected.
</P>
<P>
This was expressed by Russian First Deputy Foreign Minister
Alexander Avdeyev and Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic
after their meeting here.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press afterwards, Avdeyev noted that the
biggest problem at present is attempts to split Kosovo from
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Certain peace-keeping operations in Kosovo by western nations,
he added, in fact work to split Yugoslavia, by violating the
resolution and other international principles.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Jovanovic noted that only on the basis of
respecting the state sovereignty and territorial integrity of
Yugoslavia, only through the comprehensive participation of the
United Nations and other international organizations, could the
relevant U.N. resolutions on Kosovo be fully carried out.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out the task for U.N. in Kosovo now is to protect
residents of all ethnics, end terrorism, crimes, anarchism and
disarm the "Kosovo Liberation Army."
</P>
<P>
Avdeyev, who arrived here Sunday, is the first high-ranking
Russian official visiting Yugoslavia since NATO ended its bombing.
</P>
<P>
Under the resolution 1244, adopted on June 10, the U.N. mission
entered Kosovo on June 15. 
</P>
