<HEADLINE> Christie Drugs Clearance Sparks IAAF Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Christie, the men's 100 meters champion at the 1992 Olympics,
has been freed from the suspension imposed on him when it was
revealed he had tested positive for nandrolone.
</P>
<P>
But while the 39-year-old sprinter was celebrating the verdict
of the three-man disciplinary committee, the IAAF, world governing
body of the sport, made it clear the case is far from closed.
</P>
<P>
Istvan Gyulai, IAAF general secretary, said: "It's written in
this UK Athletics press release that it has not been proven beyond
reasonable doubt that the substance present in the sample was
derived from the prohibited substance.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is that the IAAF says that if it is in your organs
and in your body it doesn't matter where it's coming from. It is
the athlete's duty to prove that it is there for natural reasons
and produced from the body.
</P>
<P>
"If it is coming from a prohibited substance or anybody who's
trying to manipulate something, it just doesn't make any
difference.That is the problem and this will probably be taken
into account by the IAAF doping commission.
</P>
<P>
"I think everybody who loves athletics hopes that it is, but it
is possible that it is not the end of the matter," he said.
</P>
<P>
Christie, currently filming a new television series, was
delighted to hear the result of Friday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
"I was always confident of this outcome having maintained from
the outset that I had done nothing wrong," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I'm relieved that the disciplinary committee in their findings
has shown that they totally support me in this. I should like to
pass on my thanks to the public, my friends and colleagues who
have given me their full support during this distressing time. I'm
looking forward to getting on with my life and with the
broadcasting career I've enjoyed since retiring from athletics,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
