<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ningxia Becomes China's Leading Energy Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region
in northwest China has been transformed into the country's leading
energy base after a series of high profile projects were launched
in the last five decades.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River, China's second longest, runs through the 60,
000-square-kilometer region, bringing the potential of three
million kw of water energy.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the region is estimated to have probable coal
reserves of 200 billion tons, ranking fifth in China. The newly
opened Lingwu Coalfield alone has a proved coal reserve of 27
billion tons, equivalent to the total reserves of the three
provinces in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia is also rich in oil and gas. The Shaanxi-Gasu-Ningxia
Gasfield is the country's largest of its kind with a gas reserve
of 40 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
However, the rich energy resources there were unable to be
developed and utilized in old China. The region had only one power
plant 64 years ago. It was equipped with a 75-kw generator which
used to serve the needs of the Dowager Cixi of the Qing Dynasty (
1644-1911) and which was later carried to Ningxia on the back of a
camel. All the electricity the plant produced was supplied to a
tiny number of people at the upper levels in those days.
</P>
<P>
By 1949 when the People's Republic of China was founded,
Ningxia could only produce 20,000 tons of coal and no more than
100,000 kwh of electricity a year.
</P>
<P>
The central government invested heavily through the 1960s and
1970s in building three large mineral production zones, the
Qingtongxia Water Control Project and the Shizuishan Thermal Power
Plant in Ningxia, laying a solid foundation for a state-class
energy base there.
</P>
<P>
More infrastructure projects were built in this ethnic area
when China began to put its emphasis of economic development in
the central and western parts in recent years.
</P>
<P>
At present, Ningxia churns out 17 million tons of coal a year,
850 times the figure of 50 years ago while its annual electricity
production averages 11.5 billion kwh, with the present daily
electricity production 314 times more than its annual output in
1949.
</P>
<P>
The region has now set up an industrial system which includes
metallurgical, chemical and coal sectors.
</P>
<P>
"Ningxia will also build a number of key projects including two
water control projects across the Yellow River and a thermal power
base at the turn of this century," said Xiang Zongxi, director of
the Regional Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chinese economists believe Ningxia will play a
bigger role in the national economic development upon full
operation of the newly built and expanded projects in the next
couple of years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kelly Acknowledges Shearer Jibe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shearer said after the Wembley game that he did not "need to
answer to anyone, least of all discredited people," when asked if
his goals had been the perfect riposte to his critics.
</P>
<P>
Kelly acknowledged the comment could have been a response to
his biography in which he exposed Shearer's alleged ultimatum to
quit the 1998 World Cup if he had been charged by the FA over a
kicking incident involving Leicester's Neil Lennon.
</P>
<P>
Former Newcastle star Malcolm Macdonald also hit out at Shearer
in a newspaper last week, claiming he was unfit to captain his
country.
</P>
<P>
Kelly said: "It is highly likely he was talking about me. He
said journalists and discredited people. I suppose it's me or
Malcolm Macdonald.
</P>
<P>
"I don't regard myself as discredited but if he regards the
fact that I resigned from the FA as bringing discredit upon myself
then that is his opinion. It doesn't cause me any unrest."
</P>
<P>
Kelly quit Lancaster Gate last year after a vote of no
confidence from the executive committee followed allegations of a
cash-for-votes deal reputedly struck by Kelly and FA chairman
Keith Wiseman with the Welsh FA.
</P>
<P>
Now Kelly's book "Sweet FA", which lifts the lid on a number of
controversial goings-on behind the doors of the FA's headquarters,
has been launched in the week England face their two crucial
qualifying games for Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
But Kelly, speaking on Talk Radio, claimed he had no control
over the timing of the launch or the book's serialisation in a
national paper.
</P>
<P>
"It didn't appear to do Alan Shearer any harm and there are far
bigger things that are going to rock the boat if the boat is going
to be rocked," he added.
</P>
<P>
"It's unfortunate if in some respects it caused some upset
during an important time but it is outside my control," he added.
</P>
