<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remote Part Of Northwest China Getting Closer To Modern World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chairman of China's
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region Ma Qizhi told Xinhua recently that
the remote region is getting closer to the modern world after 50
years of efforts, since the new China was established in 1949.
</P>
<P>
When the American journalist Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star
Over China, visited China in 1936, it took him over 30 days to get
here from northern China, Ma says, but he could even get here from
the United States in just one day, now.
</P>
<P>
When the new China was established, there was not a single
railway line in Ningxia and roads were only used by horse carts
and people on foot, he recalls. Humans and horses were beasts of
burden. Ningxia now has several railway lines and expressways
being built to link Ningxia's cities with each other and with
northern China, and eight big bridges across the Yellow River, to
overcome geographical disadvantages.
</P>
<P>
It used to take much longer than a year for a Moslem to make
the pilgrimage to Saudi Arabia's holy city of Mecca. Hedong
Airport in the capital Yinchuan now handles jumbo jets and the
eight airlines here now make it possible to reach major Chinese
cities in less than half a day.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous region was established in 1958. Since then the
Central Government has adopted preferential policies for it and
allocated large sums to assist construction work, Ma says. Annual
state subsidies amount to as much as a billion yuan, making a
great contribution to modernization.
</P>
<P>
Communications cables stretch for more than 1,000 kilometers to
all cities in the region and connecting up with more than 150
countries on the information highway. With the rapid development
of infrastructure, more enterprises in the region have opened
their doors to foreign markets and more foreign investors have
come to the region, Ma says.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia now has economic and trade relations with over 60
countries and regions and trade worth more than 300 million U.S.
dollars. Tourism is also developing, and 1.9 million people
visited the region in 1998, bringing in 480 million yuan in
earnings.
</P>
<P>
To cut the distance between this formerly remote part of China
and the rest of the world's economic development, Ningxia has
decided to spend more than 10 billion yuan annually on
infrastructure to provide a solid foundation for 21st century
development, Ma says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
