<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Marking the first visit of a Chinese head of state to
Australia, President Jiang Zemin arrived Melbourne last night,
vowing to bolster ties between the two Asian-Pacific nations.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement upon arriving at Australia's second-
largest city, Jiang said his present visit to Australia is aimed
at enhancing friendship, deepening cooperation and opening up the
way to the future with the interests of the Asian-Pacific region
in mind.
</P>
<P>
-- The leading newspaper carried a commentator's article today
condemning Taiwan's Lee Teng-hui and his "two states" remarks.
</P>
<P>
It outlined the history of Lee Teng-hui's approach to the "two-
states" remarks, and pointed out that the intention of his remarks
like "one country, two governments," or "one country, two
political entities" is to defy and abandon the "one China"
principle.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The International Agency for the Prevention of Blindness (
IAPB) opened its sixth general assembly yesterday in Beijing,
which is the first event of this kind ever held in China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin sent a congratulation letter to
the assembly, saying the Chinese government will sign the "Vision
2020" manifesto, with solemn promise of helping prevent and cure
blindness.
</P>
<P>
Jiang described the Vision 2020 coalition as "a measure of
great significance to promote global blindness prevention and
treatment to reduce the harm of visual impairment".
</P>
<P>
-- China supports Cote d'Ivoire's bid to host the next
Universal Postal Congress (UPC) and wished it success, said
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji and Vice-President Hu Jintao yesterday
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders made the remarks when holding separate meetings
with Daniel Kablan Duncan, prime minister of Cote d'Ivoire, who
arrived in the Chinese capital Sunday to attend the ongoing 22nd
UPC.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Striving to guarantee maritime safety, Chinese police
officers are cracking down on modern-day pirates and have already
nailed five major cases, said An Xiaohui, deputy section chief of
the Criminal Investigation Bureau under the Ministry of Public
Security.
</P>
<P>
Rogue pirating in Southeast Asian waters has raised strong
condemnation and great concern from the international community.
In all, 51 percent of the 47 cases the world witnessed between
April and June happened there, according to a notice issued by
International Maritime Organization.
</P>
<P>
-- A Beijing 2008 Olympic Bid Committee, consisting of 76
members, was officially established yesterday. The committee will
be headed by Beijing Mayor Liu Qi, with Wu Shaozu, director of the
State Sports General Administration (SSGA) as executive chairman.
Yuan Weimin, deputy director of the SSGA, and Liu Jingmin, vice-
mayor of Beijing, are executive vice-chairmen.  
</P>
