<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Loans to Help Poor Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A loan system for financially
strapped college students has kicked off in eight cities with the
start of the autumn school term, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The paper quotes an official from the Ministry of Education as
saying that a total of 700 million yuan (about 84 million U.S.
dollars) is set aside to help cash-poor students in 136
institutions of higher learning. The colleges and universities are
affiliated with 39 ministries and commissions under the State
Council or bureaus and corporations adjoining ministries.
</P>
<P>
The system will begin in Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin, Chongqing,
Wuhan Shenyang, Xi'an and Nanjing, which have the greatest number
of institutions of higher learning. The program will enter more
areas within the next few years, with the goal of helping poor
students complete college careers.
</P>
<P>
The loan system will offer students a 50-percent discount on
interest repayment, with the state picking up the tab for the
remainder. They are required to repay loans with discount
interests within four years of graduation.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education and the Industrial and Commercial
Bank of China have worked out regulations for implementing the
system.
</P>
<P>
In principle, each student can apply for loans once a year
during a college study career.
</P>
<P>
Students' loans may vary with tuition fees of different
universities and regions. Generally, a student can obtain a
maximum of 8,000 yuan (about 960 U.S. dollars) each year.
</P>
<P>
An average of 20 percent of college students in China have
financial problems, says the paper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
