<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seles Beats Capriati in U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Fourth seed Monica Seles
outplayed fellow American Jennifer Capriati 6-4, 6-3 Monday in a
rematch of their semifinal classic of eight years ago and advanced
to the quarterfinals of the U.S. Open Tennis Championships.
</P>
<P>
Seles needed only one hour and 14 minutes to dispatch Capriati.
Capriati put in a gallant effort, fighting back from service
breaks in each set, only to be broken once again by Sele's severe
firepower.
</P>
<P>
Another rematch of note took place on the men's side as second
seed Andre Agassi of the United States stormed past unseeded
Arnaud Clement of France 6-4, 6-4, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Clement came within two points of defeating Agassi in the
second round at the French Open, but Agassi managed to prevail in
five sets and eventually took the title. Agassi was in control the
entire way Monday, dominating the match and keeping Clement on the
defensive with penetrating groudstrokes.
</P>
<P>
In other women's four-round action, second and defending
champion Lindsay Davenport of the United States takes on ninth
seed Julie Halard-Decugis of France Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Fifth seed Mary Pierce of France beat unseeded Sabine Appelmans
of Belgium 6-3, 7-6 (8-6), while seventh seed Serena Williams, who
survived a third-round scare from Belgium's Kim Clijsters Saturday,
went the distance against Monday before ousting No. 16 Conchita
Martinez of Spain 4-6, 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Unseeded Nicolas Escude of France provided the only surprise of
the day as he ousted 10th seed Marcelo Rios of Chile 6-2, 6-3, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
In other men's action, third seed Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia
knocked out close friend and French Open finalist Andrei Medvedev
of Ukraine 7-6 (7-5), 6-1, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
Also, No. 12 Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands faces Vince
Spadea of the United States, who has pulled out two straight five-
set matches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
