<DOCNO> XIE19990907.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Meets Security Council Mission to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Monday that he and Indonesian
President Habibie agreed on the need for further urgent measures
to restore law and order in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after meeting with the five members of a
Security Council mission which goes to Jakarta Monday night to
seek ways of halting violence in East Timor following the
announcement of the August 30 vote which favors its independence.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that such steps will have an immediate positive effect,
for it is essential that militia violence and intimidation be
brought under control," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The present chaos in East Timor cannot be allowed to fester
any longer," he said.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions from reporters, the secretary-general said
the world community would have to consider other measures to
assist Indonesia in meeting its obligation to keep order in East
Timor if the violence continues.
</P>
<P>
The proposal for martial law there "is on the table," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he was "extremely concerned" over recent and current
developments in East Timor. He condemned "in the strongest
possible terms" the attack on a Red Cross compound in Dili,
capital of East Timor, Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said he was also outraged that internally displaced persons
were being forced by militias into trucks and taken away against
their will.
</P>
<P>
Annan has been in phone contact several times with President
Habibie on the matter and discussed the situation over the phone
with leaders of the United States, Australia, Portugal and others
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
He said the mission, initiated at a Security Council meeting
Sunday night, would "relay its (the council's) serious concern to
the government of Indonesia regarding current developments."
</P>
<P>
Led by the permanent representative of Namibia to the U.N., the
team is composed of the permanent representatives of Malaysia,
Slovenia and Britain as well as the deputy permanent
representative of the Netherlands to the U.N., it was announced
earlier Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
