MOSCOW -- Russia said Monday that it is ready to resume talks
with the U.S. on creating missile attack early warning centers.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev will raise the question with his
U.S. counterpart, William Cohen, when the latter visits Moscow on
September 12. "The time and very possibility of resuming Russian-
American consultations on early warning centers will depend on the
outcome of the talks between the heads of the defense agencies,"
the official said. (Russia-US-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- The second rebel leader of the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC) Monday voiced misgivings about the new
army chief as the fledgling peace process in the war-torn central
African country got underway.
</P>
<P>
"General Sylvestre Luesha is very close to (DRC President)
Laurent Kabila. He is more of a Mai Mai organizer than a military
man," South African Press Association quoted Ernest Wamba dia
Wamba, head of the Goma faction of the Congolese Rally for
Democracy (RCD), as saying in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Kabila announced Luesha's appointment as new head of the DRC
armed forces on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wamba, who held talks with President Thabo Mbeki on Sunday,said
he would not go as far as the Kisangani RCD faction to demand the
removal of Luesha to avoid a resumption of hostilities. (Congo-
Democratic-Rebel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Botswanan President Festus Mogae is to end the
four-day state of emergency on Tuesday when he signs into law an
amendment to include about 60,000 registered voters on the voters'
roll, a presidential spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency, which was declared last Thursday, was
for the sole purpose of being able to recall the parliament to
amend the act, under which the aforementioned voters could not be
included on the roll because of a writ issued for the October 16
election before their names were published for inspection. (
Botswana-Election) (
</P>
</TEXT>
