<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Shipowners Bar Danube Navigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Romanian shipowners and
river harbor operators Monday blocked navigation on the Danube
river for all vessels as a protest against the delay of restoring
traffic on the international river.
</P>
<P>
According to Mihai Razi, president of the Trade Union
Federation of Romanian Navigators, shipowners and harbor operators
will bar the Danube till September 8. They made the move also in
hope for getting financial support from the Romanian state to pay
wage arrears, as well as the suspension and/or rescheduling of
debts the commercial companies afflicted with the Kosovo war owe
to the budget, Mihai Razi added.
</P>
<P>
Unless the government gives no sign, by September 9, concerning
their claims, shipowners and river harbor operators will block the
Danube for an indefinite time-span, warned Mihai Razi.
</P>
<P>
According to the Association of Shipowners and river harbor
operators, almost 85 percent of the Romanian river commodities
freights are bound to Hungary, Austria and Germany and use the
Yugoslav Danube waters. The current navigation is completely
paralyzed, in this sector, in response to the deistruction of four
bridges out of which two in Novi Sad and one in Backa Palanka and
the fourth in Sombor, by the NATO strikes.
</P>
<P>
Romanian shipowners and river harbor operators score monthly
losses ranging between 100,000 and 600,000 U.S. dollars, besides
that they must cancel several contracts which brings penalties,
extra taxes and expenditure to the vessels and crews blocked in
several Danube harbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
